{"title_page": "Larry Crowder", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Senator\n| name = Larry Crowder\n| image = Sen. Larry Crowder.jpg\n| state_senate = Colorado\n| state = Colorado\n| district = 35th\n| term_start = January 15, 2013\n| predecessor = [[Joyce Foster]]\n| successor =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Otero County, Colorado]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| spouse = Cheri\n| children = 2\n| residence = [[Alamosa, Colorado]]\n| profession = \n| religion =\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n\n'''Larry Crowder''' is a Republican legislator in the American [[Colorado|State of Colorado]]. Elected to the [[Colorado Senate]] in 2012, he currently represents Senate District 35 which encompasses parts of [[Pueblo County, Colorado|Pueblo County]], and all of [[Alamosa County, Colorado|Alamosa County]], [[Baca County, Colorado|Baca County]], [[Bent County, Colorado|Bent County]], [[Conejos County, Colorado|Conejos County]], [[Costilla County, Colorado|Costilla County]], [[Crowley County, Colorado|Crowley County]], [[Custer County, Colorado|Custer County]], [[Huerfano County, Colorado|Huerfano County]], [[Kiowa County, Colorado|Kiowa County]], [[Las Animas County, Colorado|Las Animas County]], [[Mineral County, Colorado|Mineral County]], [[Otero County, Colorado|Otero County]], [[Prowers County, Colorado|Prowers County]], [[Rio Grande County, Colorado|Rio Grande County]], and [[Saguache County, Colorado|Saguache County]].\n\n==Biography and early career==\nCrowder <ref>{{Cite web|title = About Senator Crowder|url = http://senatorlarrycrowderclientmu.uxinetwork.com/about-us/|website = Senator Larry Crowder|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> was raised in [[Manzanola, Colorado|Manzanola]] near [[La Junta, Colorado]].  When he was 15 years old, his father was killed in an auto accident. His mother Fern, a housewife, was left to raise seven children on her own.\n\nCrowder graduated from Manzanola High School in 1966. He enlisted in the United States Army in 1968. He served his country in Vietnam and was honorably discharged in 1971 as a disabled American veteran.\n\nAfter discharge from the Army, Crowder married Cheri and the couple lived in Denver. The couple had two children: Patrick in 1974 and Dave in 1976.\n\nIn 1976, the family moved to [[Alamosa, Colorado]] where Crowder bought a small farm and started a trenching and excavating company. The business contracted with the phone company to bury telephone lines in Southern Colorado. The advent of fiber optic technology in the late 1990s made the excavating company's services obsolete.\n\nIn need of income, Crowder began working for the postal service. In 2008, he retired from the postal service and began working as the Veterans Service Officer for [[Rio Grande County, Colorado|Rio Grande County]] in Colorado.\n\nIn 2000 Crowder was elected as the Chairman of the South Central Workforce Board, a position that he held through 2010. Beginning in 2004, he was also elected to serve as the Alamosa County Land Use Board Chair, a position that he continues to serve. Crowder also serves on the Alamosa County Draft Board (2008\u2013present) and acted as the Alamosa County GOP Chair from 2004 to 2010. He is active with the Military Color Guard, [http://www.coloradocattle.org/ Colorado Cattlemen's Association] and with various other community initiatives in Southern Colorado.\n\nCrowder continues to farm and live in Alamosa, Colorado with his wife.\n\n==Colorado State Senate==\n\n===2012 Election===\nDue to reapportionment and population shifts, Senate District 35, which used to be located in the urban Denver area, was relocated to the rural eastern plains. District 35 was drawn into the middle of former Senate Districts 1 and 2, which includes Walsenburg, Saguache, Lamar and the surrounding areas.\n\nCrowder faced no opposition in the primary elections, but faced [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent Crestina Martinez in the general election. Crowder won the election with a 1,672 vote margin.<ref name=\"Personal Bio\">{{cite news |title = Denver Post Election Results|url= http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-senate/2012/|work=Denver Post |accessdate=2012-11-27 }}</ref>\n\n===2013 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=Crowder\n|Year=2015\n|Bill Number 1=\n|Bill Number 2=\n|Bill Number 3=\n|Bill Number 4=\n|Bill Number 5=\n|Bill Number 6=\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2015a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont2/D05CF73CA79A4D0387257DF7005BFCF2/$FILE/1380_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= \n|Bill Link 3= \n|Bill Link 4= \n|Bill Link 5= \n|Bill Link 6= \n|Bill Status 1=\n|Bill Status 2= \n|Bill Status 3=\n|Bill Status 4=\n|Bill Status 5=\n|Bill Status 6=\n|Bill Title 1=\n|Bill Title 2= \n|Bill Title 3=\n|Bill Title 4= \n|Bill Title 5=\n|Bill Title 6= \n}}\n\nFor the 2013 legislative session, Senator Crowder was appointed to serve on the Health and Human Services Committee, as well as the State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee. In April 2013, Crowder became the only [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the State Senate to vote to expand [[Medicaid]] under the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref name=\"AD041613\">{{cite news\n | title = Medicaid expansion, Fort Lyons, rape kit measures all move forward at Capitol\n | work = [[KDVR]]\n | date = April 15, 2013\n | url = http://kdvr.com/2013/04/15/medicaid-expansion-fort-lyons-rape-kit-measures-all-move-forward-at-capitol/\n| accessdate = April 16, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 Legislative Session ===\nIn the 2014 legislative session, Crowder sponsored [http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2014a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont2/1E390935433C251F87257C620063CC4A/$FILE/1328_enr.pdf legislation] to provide grants to public utilities that pay for broadband development in rural communities through the Connect Colorado Broadband Act.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Governor Signs Colorado Broadband Expansion|url = http://denver.cbslocal.com/2014/05/09/governor-to-sign-colorado-broadband-expansion/|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> He also worked to create jobs and preserve historic structures by sponsoring the Job Creation & Main Street Revitalization Act <ref>{{Cite web|title = Colorado Jobs & Main Street Revitalization Act (Colorado State Tax-Credit)|url = http://coloradopreservation.org/news/colorado-job-creation-main-street-revitalization-act/|website = coloradopreservation.org|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> that brought $15 million in economic development to Southern Colorado.\n\n=== 2015 Legislative Session ===\nDuring the 2015 legislative session, Crowder sponsored legislation to expedite the licensing process to become an [[advanced practice nurse]],<ref>[http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2015a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont2/E8468619502FF11787257DE100000435/$FILE/197_enr.pdf]</ref> to offer [http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2015a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont2/3ED770D2B69ADB0087257DEB007F32FA/$FILE/222_01.pdf tax incentives] to providers who bring broadband services to rural areas and to protect Colorado's [http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2015a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont2/44CE371FA47B8C2187257D95001D8EC3/$FILE/121_enr.pdf drinking water], [http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2015a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont2/D05CF73CA79A4D0387257DF7005BFCF2/$FILE/1380_01.pdf watersheds] and ecologically sensitive areas. He was also named the [http://coruralhealth.org/2015/08/ceo-update-appreciation-2.html 2015 Rural Health Champion]<ref>{{Cite web|title = CEO Update: Appreciation {{!}} Colorado Rural Health Center|url = http://coruralhealth.org/2015/08/ceo-update-appreciation-2.html|website = coruralhealth.org|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> by the Colorado Rural Health Center.\n\n=== 2016 Legislative Session ===\nIn 2016, Crowder sponsored SB 74 aimed at expanding voting options  for rural voters.<ref>{{Cite web|title = At the State Capitol: State Sen. Larry Crowder\u2019s bill to alter current election law passed Senate State|url = http://www.chieftain.com/news/region/4435656-120/state-bill-crowder-rural|access-date = 2016-02-14|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160213092836/http://www.chieftain.com/news/region/4435656-120/state-bill-crowder-rural|archive-date = 2016-02-13|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n===2018 Legislative Session===\n\nDuring the 2018 Legislative Session Senator Crowder focused attention of health care matters and veterans\u2019 issues. He ran Senate Bill 112 which would have created a grant program to help support non-profits that provide mental health care for veterans. He also ran Senate Bill 54 to put a cap on fee increases for assisted living facilities and Senate Bill 71 that allowed a task force to continue studying substance abuse issues. Senator Crowder also ran a bill that would have exempted used vehicles from the state sales and use tax.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Colorado General Assembly|url =https://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/larry-w-crowder }}</ref>\n\n== Sexual assault allegations ==\n\nBetween November 2017 and April 2018, six Colorado state legislators were accused of sexual harassment covering a range of allegations and circumstances.\n<ref>[http://coloradocommunitymedia.com/stories/sen-daniel-kagan-formally-accused-sexual-harassment-womens-bathroom-martinez-humenik,261134 State Senator Kagan formally accused of harassment Lawmaker alleged to have been in womens restroom multiple times at Capitol], ''[[Colorado Community Media]]'', Ellis Arnold, April 20, 2018. Retrieved July 21, 2018.</ref> Senator Crowder was accused by [[Susan Lontine]], a Democratic State Representative from Denver, of pinching her buttocks and making sexually inappropriate comments while on the House floor.  He apologized, though he did not take steps to acknowledge or change his behavior.<ref>[https://www.denverpost.com/2018/02/09/larry-crowder-sexual-harassment-complaint-kevin-grantham/ Another Colorado lawmaker\u2019s credible sexual harassment complaint emerges, as Democrats mount pressure for top Republican to act. Susan Lontine, a Denver Democrat, came forward with complaint against Republican Sen. Larry Crowder after concern with Grantham\u2019s handling of the issue], ''[[Denver Post]]'', John Frank, Jesse Paul, Brian Eason, February 9, 2018. Retrieved July 21, 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kdvr.com/2018/02/08/another-lawmaker-at-the-capitol-accuses-a-fellow-lawmaker-of-sexual-harassment/ |title=Another lawmaker accused of sexual harassment |date=February 9, 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref> \n\nColorado State Senate President Republican [[Kevin Grantham]] issued a statement when the story was published, saying, \"We take every allegation of harassment or misconduct seriously. We ask those who feel they have been victims of harassment or inappropriate behavior at the General Assembly to file an official complaint, in confidence that their anonymity and rights will be protected. Going forward, Senate Republican leaders cannot and will not be responding to unsubstantiated or anonymous allegations against members appearing in the press, which the existing complaint process is designed to handle. This process exists to protect confidentiality, respect the rights of both accuser and accused, rigorously review the facts, give a fair hearing to all sides, and impose penalties proportionate to any confirmed offense.\"<ref>[http://www.kunc.org/post/colorado-senators-baumgardner-and-tate-named-allegations-sexual-harassment Colorado Senators Baumgardner And Tate Named In Allegations Of Sexual Harassment], ''[[KUNC]]'', Bente Birkeland, November 16, 2017. Retrieved June 24, 2018.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2013A/cslFrontPages.nsf/HomeSplash?OpenForm Colorado General Assembly Website]\n* [http://coloradosenatenews.com/ Colorado Senate News]\n\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crowder, Larry}}