y]] (loan)\n|          caps7 = 17\n|         goals7 = 0\n|         years8 = 2009\u20132010\n|         clubs8 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|          caps8 = 54\n|         goals8 = 2\n|         years9 = 2011\u20132012\n|         clubs9 = [[Muangthong United F.C.|Muangthong United]]\n|          caps9 = 34\n|         goals9 = 1\n|         years10= 2012\u20132013\n|         clubs10= [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]]\n|          caps10= 64\n|         goals10= 2\n| nationalyears1 =\n|  nationalteam1 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n|  nationalcaps1 = \u2013\n| nationalgoals1 = \u2013 \n| nationalyears2 =\n|  nationalteam2 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n|  nationalcaps2 = \u2013\n| nationalgoals2 = \u2013\n| nationalyears3 =\n|  nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]\n|  nationalcaps3 = \u2013\n| nationalgoals3 = \u2013\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\u2013\n|  nationalteam4 = [[Pakistan national football team|Pakistan]]\n|  nationalcaps4 = 22\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| club-update    = 19 May 2019\n| nationalteam-update = 12 September 2018\n|         years11= 2014\u20132016 \n|         clubs11= [[Pahang FA]]\n|          caps11= 94\n|         goals11= 13\n|         years12= 2017\n|         clubs12= [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n|          caps12= 10\n|         goals12= 1\n|         years13= 2017\u2013\n|         clubs13= [[Southern District FC|Southern]]\n|          caps13= 32\n|         goals13= 0\n}}\n'''Zeshan Rehman''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0630\u064a\u0634\u0627\u0646 \u0631\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0646}}}}; born 14 October 1983)<ref name=\"SW\"/> is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Hong Kong Premier League]] club [[Southern District FC|Southern]].\n\nHe was the first [[British Asian]] to start a [[Premier League]] match and is the first to have played in all four divisions of professional football in England. He also plays for the [[Pakistan national football team]] and was the first Pakistani international footballer to play professional football in England, Thailand, Hong Kong and Malaysia, as well as the first Pakistani international to play in the [[AFC Cup]]. He started his career at [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and made a total of 30 appearances, having loan spells at [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] and [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]. A transfer to [[Queens Park Rangers]] followed and he went on to make 50 appearances for the club. During his three years there he went on loan to Brighton & Hove Albion, [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] and Bradford City, moving permanently to the latter on a free transfer in June 2009. Having previously represented [[England national football team|England]] at [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] levels, in 2005 he made his debut for Pakistan.\n\nOutside of his playing career, Rehman is known for being an ambassador for [[Kick It Out (football's equality and inclusion campaign)|Kick It Out]] and the [[Show Racism the Red Card]] campaign, and his efforts to help British Asian players.\n\n==Early life==\nRehman was born on 14 October 1983 in [[Birmingham]].<ref name=\"back to my roots\"/> His father is Khalid Rehman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rehman craving Fulham escape|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/features/rehman-craving-fulham-escape#:oyTFFwtriFDHWA|publisher=Four Four Two|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> As a child in Birmingham he played for his local [[Sunday league football|Sunday league]] team, Kingshurst.<ref name=\"back to my roots\"/> He was brought up in the [[Aston]] area of the city and often played football on the streets in addition to representing his school, his district and his county in football.<ref name=\"people93463\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Fulham===\nWhen he was just twelve years old he was spotted by a [[scout (sport)|scout]]<ref name=\"people93463\">{{cite news | title = The Premiership's first asian star: Zesh Rehman |work=[[The People]] | date = 17 May 2009 | url = http://www.people.co.uk/sport/jsp/tm_headline=the-premiership-s-first-asian-star-zesh-rehman&method=full&objectid=21361784&siteid=93463-name_page.html | last = Fletcher | first = James | accessdate =5 June 2009}}</ref> and moved with his family to London where he joined the [[Fulham Academy]]. He progressed through the junior, youth and reserve teams at [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], which led him to sign his first professional contract.<ref name=\"BFC-programme\">{{cite journal | title = A dedication to inspire \u2013 Will to succeed sees Zesh become a role model | journal=Up The Pool | volume = 2008\u201309 season | issue = Blackpool vs Crystal Palace | pages = 34\u201337 | publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] | location = [[Blackpool]] | date = 25 October 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fruit of the Academy|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2002/february/11/fruit-of-the-academy|publisher=Fulham Official Website|date=11 February 2002|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> Although a [[defender (association football)|centre back]] by trade, Rehman was used as a [[defensive midfielder|holding midfielder]] as well as [[right back]] in his career at Fulham.<ref name=\"Transfer latest\">{{cite web|title=Zesh Rehman|url=http://www.fulhamweb.co.uk/player/461/zesh-rehman.aspx|publisher=Fulham|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Craven Cottage.JPG|thumb|left|Rehman started his career at Craven Cottage]]\n\nIn the [[2003\u201304 in English football|2003\u201304 season]], Rehman made his professional debut on 23 September 2003 in a 1\u20130 defeat away to [[Wigan Athletic]] in the second round of the [[Football League Cup]], coming on as a substitute for [[Junichi Inamoto]] after 57 minutes.<ref name=\"One\"/> Six days later, he was sent on loan to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] of the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]], initially for one month until November.<ref name=\"bbc3149526\">{{cite news | title = Brighton seal Rehman deal |publisher=BBC    | date = 29 September 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/3149526.stm | accessdate =26 October 2008}}</ref> He scored on his debut for the club on 30 September, concluding a 3\u20131 away win at [[Rushden & Diamonds]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rushden 1\u20133 Brighton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/3139016.stm|accessdate=29 July 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=30 September 2003}}</ref> On 11 October, he opened a 3\u20130 win against [[Grimsby Town]] at the [[Withdean Stadium]], finishing a corner by [[Leon Knight]] in [[Bob Booker]]'s first match in charge.<ref>{{cite news|title=October 11: Albion 3 Grimsby 0|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/5102855.October_11__Albion_3_Grimsby_0/|accessdate=29 July 2015|work=The Argus|date=14 October 2003}}</ref> Rehman's loan was extended to three months ending in January 2004.<ref name=\"bbc3325679\">{{cite news | title = Duo stay with Brighton |publisher=BBC    | date = 16 December 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/3325679.stm | accessdate =26 October 2008}}</ref> He made eleven league appearances, scoring two goals.<ref name=\"back to my roots\"/>\n\nHe made his [[Premier League]] debut for Fulham in a goalless draw at [[Anfield]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 17 April 2004, replacing [[Bobby Petta]] for the final minute of the match.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liverpool 0\u20130 Fulham|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3615831.stm|accessdate=29 July 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=17 April 2004}}</ref> In doing so, he garnered media attention from [[British Asian]] groups by being the first British Asian player to play in the top division of English football.<ref name=\"BFC-programme\"/> In June, Rehman signed a new contract, to keep him until 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rehman signs contract|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2004/june/04/rehman-signs-contract|publisher=Fulham Official Website|date=4 June 2004|accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September 2005 in the League Cup second round, Rehman scored his only goal for Fulham, opening a 5\u20134 extra-time win over [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] at [[Craven Cottage]] by heading in [[Hei\u00f0ar Helguson]]'s cross.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/4258578.stm\n|title=Fulham 5\u20134 Lincoln (aet)\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=21 September 2005 |accessdate=19 November 2009}}</ref> In January 2006 he signed for [[Football League Championship|Championship]] club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] on loan for the rest of the season as defensive cover for the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Earnshaw escapes Albion with \u00a33.5m move to Norwich|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/01/newsstory.sport5|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He made five starts for them.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\">{{cite news | title = Soccerbase profile | publisher=Soccerbase | url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=36002 | accessdate =23 June 2009}}</ref> Having made 30 appearances in all competitions for Fulham, 26 from the starting line-up and four as a substitute, Rehman had to consider his options if he was to get regular football. Although he had two years remaining on his contract, he wanted to play regular first team football, and as a result, he decided to spend the next two seasons getting as much experience as possible.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web | last = Rehman | first = Zesh | title = Zesh Rehman biography | url=http://www.zeshrehman.com/biography.htm | publisher=Zeshrehman.com | accessdate =15 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Queens Park Rangers===\n\nOn 8 August 2006, just prior to the start of the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307 season]], Rehman signed for Championship club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] (QPR) from Fulham on a three-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref name=\"bbc5256446\">{{cite news | title = QPR swoop to sign Fulham's Rehman |publisher=BBC    | date = 8 August 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/q/qpr/5256446.stm | accessdate =25 October 2008}}</ref> In his first season at QPR, Rehman made 27 appearances.<ref name=\"Transfer latest\"/>\n\nTowards the end of the season Rehman was sent on loan to former club Brighton & Hove Albion for a month where he gained more first team football experience.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Fulham star Zesh Rehman: Asia was my destiny, Malaysia is my home|url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/football-asia/153/post/2052554/former-fulham-star-zesh-rehman-always-knew-asia-was-his-destiny|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on 24 March 2007 in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref name=\"Pak\">{{cite web|title=Zesh Rehman set to join top Malaysian club|url=http://article.wn.com/view/2013/12/03/Zesh_Rehman_set_to_join_top_Malaysian_club/|publisher=WN|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> He ended his loan stint by playing the full 90 minutes, and earning a [[Misconduct (association football)|yellow card]] in the process, for the final game of the [[Football League One|League One]] season in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] on 5 May 2007, claiming an assist for the opening goal.<ref>{{cite news | date = 5 May 2007 | title = Match report: Cheltenham 1\u20131 Brighton |publisher=BBC    |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/6602957.stm | accessdate =24 June 2009}}</ref> He featured in eight full games during his loan spell.<ref name=\"back to my roots\">{{cite news | last = Pope | first = Dan | title = Back to my roots \u2013 Zesh Rehman | publisher = The Club House | url = http://www.clubnewsletter.co.uk/2009/feb/zeshrehman.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20130420023617/http://www.clubnewsletter.co.uk/2009/feb/zeshrehman.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 20 April 2013 | accessdate = 26 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\nReturning to QPR at the start of the new season, chances were limited. The 3\u20131 victory over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on New Years Day 2008 was Rehman's 50th game in all competitions since leaving Fulham in 2006.<ref>{{cite news | title = QPR 3\u20131 Leicester |publisher=BBC    | date = 1 January 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/7163883.stm | accessdate =26 May 2009}}</ref> Rehman finished the 2007\u201308 season in the starting line for QPR against the Championship's new champions, [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news | title = QPR 0\u20132 West Brom |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport-old/football/2008/05/05/qpr-0-2-west-brom-115875-20406035/ | date = 5 May 2008 | accessdate =26 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Blackpool (loan)====\nRehman joined [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in a six-month loan deal on 31 July 2008, along with teammate [[Daniel Nardiello]], who joined the club on a permanent basis, while Blackpool defender [[Kaspars Gork\u0161s]] moved to QPR in exchange.<ref name=\"bbc753633\">{{cite news | title = Blackpool seal deals for QPR pair |publisher=BBC    | date = 1 August 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/blackpool/7536333.stm | accessdate =26 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"footballpakistan3070\">{{cite news | last = Ahsan | first = Ali | title = Zesh Rehman moves to Blackpool FC | publisher=footballpakistan.com | date = 31 July 2008 | url = http://www.footballpakistan.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3070&Itemid=43 | accessdate =26 October 2008}}</ref> He made his debut for Blackpool as a second-half substitute for [[Jermaine Wright]] in a 2\u20130 defeat at [[Football League Two|League Two]] club [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] in the first round of the [[2008\u201309 Football League Cup|2008\u201309 Carling Cup]] on 12 August 2008. He was used as an emergency striker due to injuries to three of the club's strikers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seasiders crash at Moss Rose|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/1691/report|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> He made his league debut the following Saturday, in a 1\u20131 draw at Norwich City, coming on early in the second half to replace defender [[Danny Coid]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Blackpool hang on for draw|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/1967/report|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThree months into his loan spell, in early October, Rehman said of his move to play for Blackpool: \"I'm quite glad to get away from all the hustle and bustle of London. I really like it up here in [[Blackpool]]; it's a good club with an ambitious young manager. Hopefully, over the next few months I can convince [[Simon Grayson]] I'm worthy of a long-term contract.\"<ref name=\"pfa-role\"/> On 31 December he returned to QPR after having made three league appearances, all of which were as a substitute.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\"/>\n\n====Bradford City (loan)====\nOn 26 January 2009, Rehman signed a loan deal with League Two club [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], which was to last until the end of the [[2008\u201309 Bradford City A.F.C. season|2008\u201309 season]].<ref name=\"bbc7851147\">{{cite news |title=Bradford sign QPR defender Rehman |publisher=BBC    |date=26 January 2009\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/7851147.stm |accessdate=26 January 2009}}</ref> Rehman had turned down a chance to move to [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] and team up with [[Mick Harford]], who was previously the assistant manager at QPR, and said he was only prepared to drop down to League Two if he joined Bradford City.<ref name=\"dt4922733\">{{cite news |title=Big Mick missed Pakistan captain |date=28 January 2009 |work=Dunstable Gazette |url= http://www.dunstabletoday.co.uk/luton-sport/Big-Mick-missed-Pakistan-captain.4922733.jp |accessdate=29 January 2009}}</ref> Rehman said of the move, \"I was only prepared to drop down the leagues to play for this club. I spoke to the manager and chairmen and I know they want to get Bradford back up to where they belong. I've been involved in relegation battles in the past and it's nice to be joining a club pushing for promotion \u2013 that's a good pressure to have.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorkss denies joining QPR for the money|url=http://www.fansnetwork.co.uk/football/queensparkrangers/news/4451/gorkss-denies-joining-qpr-for-the-money-%C3%A2%E2%82%AC%E2%80%9C-news-round-up|publisher=Fans News Network|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> He made his debut the following day in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] at [[Gigg Lane]], and in doing so became the first British Asian to play in all four divisions of professional football in England.<ref>{{cite web|title=Journeyman Zesh Rehman discusses Thailand, Pakistan and his time in England's top four divisions|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/141/asia/2012/02/22/2921053/journeyman-zesh-rehman-discusses-thailand-pakistan-and-his|publisher=Goal|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> He made his home debut on 31 January, playing at right back, in a 2\u20130 home win over [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] at [[Valley Parade]].<ref name=\"ta4092136\">{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Simon |title=Jones' luck turns as he breaks City jinx |date=2 February 2009 |work=[[Telegraph & Argus]]|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/4092136.Jones__luck_turns_as_he_breaks_City_jinx/ |accessdate=2 February 2009}}</ref> In March he turned down the chance to play for Pakistan in the [[AFC Challenge Cup|Asian Football Confederation Challenge Cup]] [[2010 AFC Challenge Cup qualification|qualifiers]] in order to help Bradford's push for promotion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rehman chooses club over country |date=27 March 2009 |publisher=BBC   |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/7967835.stm |accessdate=12 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Bradford City===\n\nAfter being released by QPR on 19 May 2009,<ref name=\"Miller among five released by QPR\">{{cite news | title = Miller among five released by QPR |publisher=BBC    |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/q/qpr/8057426.stm | date = 19 May 2009 | accessdate =26 May 2009}}</ref>\nRehman signed a two-year deal with Bradford City on 19 June, saying of the move, \"My gut feeling told me to sign for Bradford and I've absolutely no regrets. From day one I felt at home here. I'm fortunate enough to have played in all the divisions and I see this as the next step of my journey.\" The Bradford manager, [[Stuart McCall]] also revealed that Rehman had taken a large pay cut by joining the club, adding, \"Zesh is certainly not signing for Bradford for money\u2014he wants to be a success here, and it will be great to have him on board.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rehman: City move felt right|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/4446507.Rehman__City_move_felt_right/|publisher=The Telegraph and Argus|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=19 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bantams bag Rehman|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11688/5388357/bantams-bag-rehman|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=19 June 2009}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 2\u20132 draw with Barnet on 19 September 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8248975.stm |title=Barnet 2\u20132 Bradford |publisher=BBC |date=19 September 2009 |accessdate=2 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nRehman was captained the club during the 2009\u201310 season<ref>{{cite web|title=Bradford City place Zesh Rehman on transfer list|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/9251198.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> and went on to play 42 games.<ref name=\"NT\"/> He won the PFA Player in the Community awards on 25 March at The Football League Awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Footballer gives Asian youths a helping hand|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2010/oct/13/zesh-rehman-football-asian-community|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=13 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the following season new manager [[Peter Taylor (footballer, born 1953)|Peter Taylor]] kept Rehman as club captain hailing him a \"supremely professional individual and a superb ambassador for the football club\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Fulham visit brings back Rehman nightmares and 1983 memories \u2013 history|url=http://fansnetwork.co.uk/football/southampton/news/16119/fulham-visit-brings-back-rehman-nightmares-and-1983-memories--history/images/rss#skipad|publisher=Fans Network|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=2 October 2010}}</ref> Struggling to get playing time, making only 12 appearances, Rehman in an interview to ''[[BBC Radio]]'' said that he was not pleased to sit in the substitute bench in the past few matches. He also added that being the skipper of the team, his experience would help the team to perform.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bradford City place Zesh Rehman on transfer list|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/9251198.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=7 January 2016|date=2 December 2010}}</ref> For making these comments, he was stripped of his captainship and put in the transfer list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rehman slapped on transfer list|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/8716491.Rehman_slapped_on_transfer_list/|publisher=The Telegraph and Argus|accessdate=7 January 2016|date=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Muangthong United===\nRehman signed a two-year deal with Thai Premier League side [[Muangthong United F.C.|Muangthong United]] on 19 December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtutd.tv/NewsDetail.asp?id=1988 |title=\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2f\u0e23\u0e38\u0e01\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e35\u0e15\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e35\u0e40\u0e21\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e25\u0e35\u0e01 \u0e2d\u0e31\u0e07\u0e01\u0e24\u0e29 \"\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e2a \u0e40\u0e23\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e21\u0e32\u0e19\" \u0e17\u0e38\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e04\u0e48\u0e32\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14 \u0e2d\u0e14\u0e35\u0e15\u0e17\u0e35\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e15\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e07\u0e42\u0e15\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e22\u0e39 20 \u0e21\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e43\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e32\u0e17\u0e35\u0e21\u0e42\u0e25\u0e14 update 19/12/2010 17.04&nbsp;pm |date=19 December 2010 |accessdate=19 December 2010 |publisher=Muangthong United F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/8747723.Bradford_City_defender_Rehman_heads_for_Far_East/ |title=Bradford City defender Rehman heads for Far East |date=20 December 2010 |accessdate=20 December 2010 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |first=Simon |last=Parker}}</ref> He made his debut on 30 January 2011, in the King's Trophy against [[Chonburi F.C.|Chonburi Sharks]] at the [[Suphachalasai Stadium]]; his new side lost 2\u20131.<ref name=\"Pak\"/> His appearance made him the first Pakistan international to play in Thailand.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.srtrc.org/news/news-and-events?news=1882 |title=New Zesh Rehman interview |publisher=Show Racism the Red Card |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> About his debut Rehman commented \"I can honestly say I loved the experience. The passion from the 40,000 fans in the crowd made it a day to remember\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Zesh Rehman|url=http://www.srtrc.org/about/players-views?id=1881|publisher=Show Racism the Red Card|accessdate=1 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714090220/http://www.srtrc.org/about/players-views?id=1881|archive-date=14 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During his stint in the club, it was managed by English striker [[Robbie Fowler]].<ref name=\"MU\"/> He made a total of thirty league appearances for the Thai club.<ref name=\"NFT\"/>\n\n===Kitchee===\nRehman signed a deal with [[Hong Kong First Division League]] side [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]] on 11 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://paper.wenweipo.com/2012/01/11/SP1201110029.htm |script-title=zh:\u5091\u5fd7\u7f85\u81f4\u524d\u82f1\u8d85\u7403\u54e1 |date=11 January 2012 |accessdate=11 January 2012 |publisher=Wen Wei Po |language=Chinese}}</ref> He made his debut in a 2\u20131 win over [[Sun Hei SC|Sun Hei]] on 31 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/03/15/hong-kong/hkfa-1st-division/kitchee-fc/sham-shui-po-sports-/1232044/ |title=Kitchee vs. Sham Shui Po \u2013 15 March 2012 |publisher=Soccerway |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Rehman scored his first goal for his new club in the [[2012 AFC Cup|AFC Cup]] against [[S\u00f4ng Lam Ngh\u1ec7 An F.C.|S\u00f4ng Lam Ngh\u1ec7 An]] of [[Vietnam]].<ref name=\"SW\"/> Rehman won his first piece of [[Silverware (sport)|silverware]] of his Hong Kong career by playing a leading role in Kitchees 2\u20131 [[2011\u201312 Hong Kong League Cup|League Cup]] win over cloes rivals [[TSW Pegasus FC|TSW Pegasus]] at the [[Mong Kok Stadium]] on 15 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/includes_files/board_details.php?news_id=9499 |title=News : Halewinner League Cup FinalTSW Pegasus 1:2 Kitchee |publisher=HKFA |date=15 April 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/en/match_result.php?match_date=2012-04-15&match_id=10537 |title=Hong Kong Football Association Ltd |publisher=Hkfa.com |date=15 April 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Rehman helped Kitchee retain the [[Hong Kong First Division League]] title with a 4\u20131 victory over [[Biu Chun Rangers]] in the last league game to clinch the title, it was his second trophy for the club and it put them in pole position to complete the domestic treble in Hong Kong<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/asian-football/news/detail/item804597/Rehman-revels-in-Kitchee-title-success/ |title=Asian Football News &#124; Rehman revels in Kitchee title success &#124; FOX SPORTS |publisher=Espnstar.com |date=20 May 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924002334/http://www.espnstar.com/football/asian-football/news/detail/item804597/Rehman-revels-in-Kitchee-title-success/ |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Rehman and Kitchee finished the season in impressive fashion by overcoming Pegasus after [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] to win [[2011\u201312 Hong Kong FA Cup|Hong Kong FA Cup]] Final at The [[Hong Kong Stadium]]. The victory was a historic moment for the club as Kitchee were crowned domestic treble winners, a feat that has never been matched by a Hong Kong club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/includes_files/board_details.php?news_id=9632 |title=News : 2011/12 FA CupTSW Pegasus 3:3 (penalty 3:5) Kitchee |publisher=HKFA |date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/en/match_result.php?match_date=2012-05-26&match_id=10813 |title=Hong Kong Football Association Ltd |publisher=Hkfa.com |date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Rehman made it into the Hong Kong BMA First Division League team of the season at The HKFA Annual Awards dinner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/includes_files/board_details.php?news_id=9634 |title=News : 2011/12 HKFA Hong Kong Top Footballer Awards |publisher=HKFA |date=28 May 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Rehman also achieved the feat of becoming the first Pakistani player to play in AFC Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=Is AFC Champions League's flawed format hurting Pakistan's growth?|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1046743/is-afc-champions-leagues-flawed-format-hurting-pakistans-growth|publisher=Dawn|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2012 Rehman played the full game in a [[Exhibition game|pre-season friendly]] against [[Premier League]] giants [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in front of a 40,000 crowd as the Hong Kong Champions drew 2\u20132 with the Gunners at The [[Hong Kong Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/match-menu/173289/first-team/kitchee-fc-v-arsenal?tab=report |title=Kitchee FC v Arsenal &#124; Match News |publisher=Arsenal.com |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304101639/http://www.arsenal.com/match-menu/173289/first-team/kitchee-fc-v-arsenal?tab=report |archive-date=4 March 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/includes_files/board_details.php?news_id=9726 |title=News : The Hong Kong Jockey Club Charity Trust Challenge CupKitchee 2:2 Arsenal (ENG) |publisher=HKFA |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> On 11 May 2013 Rehman won the [[Hong Kong FA Cup]] through a 1\u20130 victory over last year finalist [[Sun Pegasus FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfa.com/includes_files/board_details.php?news_id=10657 |title=News : FA Cup FinalSun Pegasus 0:1 Kitchee |publisher=HKFA |date=11 May 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> On 26 May 2013 Rehman helped Kitchee beat Tuen Mun 3\u20130 in the final of the play-off to ensure his teams passage into the AFC Cup 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.hkfa.com/en/board_details.php?news_id=10692 |title=\u9999\u6e2f\u8db3\u7403\u7e3d\u6703 \u2013 \u624b\u6a5f\u7248 |publisher=M.hkfa.com |date=26 May 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Rehman played fifteen league games for the club during the 2012/13 season, which was followed by six appearances in the next season.<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n\n===Pahang FA===\nIn December 2013, Rehman signed for Malayasian club [[Pahang FA]] on a two-year contract. His former club [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]]'s president [[Ken Ng]] commented \"Zesh has contributed hugely to Kitchee's success over the last 2 years and he will be truly missed\". His new club's manager [[Zainal Abidin Hassan]] said that they were \"delighted\" as he \"has chosen to come to Pahang ahead of several other teams.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rehman makes Malayasian Super League switch|url=http://www.thepfa.com/news/2013/12/9/rehman-makes-malaysian-switch|publisher=The PFA|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> He justified his reason of joining the club as \"his destiny\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Goal Malaysia's Hotseat with Aysha Ridzuan: Zesh Rehman enjoying life with Pahang|url=http://www.goal.com/en-my/news/3902/exclusives/2014/01/22/4561161/goal-malaysias-hotseat-with-aysha-ridzuan-zesh-rehman|publisher=Goal|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> In his first season with the club, he won three trophies<ref name=\"FO\">{{cite web|title=Exclusive: One on One with Pahang FA's Zesh Rehman|url=http://www.fourthofficial.com/football/exclusive-one-on-one-with-pahang-fas-zesh-rehman/|publisher=Fourth official|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> \u2013 [[Malaysia Super League]], [[Malaysia FA Cup]] and [[Malaysia Cup]],<ref name=\"SW\"/> thus winning qualification to the [[2015 AFC Cup]].<ref name=\"FO\"/> In the cup, he played six times without scoring a goal.<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Zesh helped Pahang to finish second in the Malaysia Super League, the highest finish for the club in over a decade and in doing so became the highest goalscoring defender in the league netting 6 times, he scored 8 goals in all competitions throughout the season. Pahang also created history by reaching the AFC Cup quarter final for the first time in their history. Zesh played the majority of the season in Midfield displaying his versatility to the team, performing admirably in the holding role. He played 45 from 46 games in all competitions his best career stats in a season to date. Throughout the year he also achieved some personal milestones such as playing over 300 career games across four nations and notching up 100+ games in Asia and completing five years of playing competitive football in the Asia region. He was handed the captain badge in the beginning of their season.\n\nOn 28 June 2016, Zesh announce via his social media accounts he had amicably agreed to terminate with Pahang FC after a successful 3-year spell at the club. Zesh said, \"I  would love a future return in a coaching role, something which was offered to me at the start of this season but was not the right moment for me. I will be back to visit my sons birthplace of Kuantan. Pahang have the best fans in Malaysia & are by far the best I have played for. Leaving here on excellent terms with the hierarchy, fantastic memories & many formed friendships. Good luck to all the staff & team for the rest of the season. Thank you\". Pahang FC were equally pleased with his contribution. Club CEO and Vice President Datuk Akbar V V Abu was quoted as saying:\"Zesh served as an excellent player for Pahang for 3 years in a successful trophy winning team. His example and leadership to the young and local players was outstanding. The door for a future return is open anytime. We would love to see him back in a coaching role one day\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/football-asia/153/post/2903679/former-fulham-defender-zesh-|title=Ex-Fulham defender Zesh Rehman leaves MSL giants Pahang|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Gillingham===\n\nOn 23 February 2017, Rehman returned to English football by joining [[League One]] side [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] until the end of the 2016/17 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/news/article/2016-17/zesh-rehman-joins-the-gills-3589795.aspx|title=ZESH REHMAN JOINS THE GILLS|publisher=}}</ref> Rehman made his debut for the club in a 2\u20131 Victory over Southend, drawing praise from manager Adrian Pennock for his performance and leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/sport/pennock-gives-rehman-thumbs-up-121266/|title=Pennock gives Rehman thumbs up|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRehman was released by the club at the conclusion of the season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/news/2017/may/retained-list-announced/|title=RETAINED LIST ANNOUNCED|accessdate=2017-05-24|language=en}}</ref> He was congratulated by [[Rehman Chishti]] MP.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Southern===\nOn 14 June 2017, Rehman announced via his Twitter page that he had signed with [[Southern District FC|Southern]], returning to Hong Kong for the first time since 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rehman|first1=Zesh|url=https://twitter.com/Zesh_Rehman/status/874994059575783424|title=Zesh Rehman on Twitter: \"Delighted to have signed for #Southern FC in the Hong Kong Premier League. Looking forward to going back to the Far East. #newchallenge\"|website=Twitter|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref>\nRehman chose Southern ahead of several other offers from around the world, citing the lure of working with head coach [[Cheng Siu Chung]] as the main attraction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-Pahang captain Zesh Rehman joins Southern District in Hong Kong|url=http://www.espnfcasia.com/blog/football-asia/153/post/3143845/ex-pahang-captain-zesh-rehman-joins-southern-district-in-hong-kong|website=ESPN|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRehman originally represented England, and played for them at [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] levels.<ref>{{cite news |title = Flown From The Nest \u2013 Zesh Rehman | publisher=Ex-Canaries.co.uk | url = http://www.ex-canaries.co.uk/players/rehman.htm | accessdate =23 June 2009}}</ref> Becoming the first English-born Pakistani to don an England senior football shirt seemed too far away, however, due to lack of first team opportunities at Fulham. Due to his Pakistani parentage, and because he possessed dual Pakistani and British nationality, Rehman also qualified to represent Pakistan, and he eventually opted to play for them, as he considered it to be a more realistic option.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Neil Farrington, Daniel Kilvington, John Price|title=Race, Racism and Sports Journalism|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415676403|page=126}}</ref> A lot of British Asian groups were against this and wanted him to fight more for an England place to set a standard for English-Asian youth.<ref name=\"pfa-role\"/>\n\nIt was, however, an unrealistic aspiration.<ref name=\"pfa-role\"/> With that in mind, and with the blessings of his father, Rehman was approached by Malik Riaz Hai Naveed a young football manager and made his international debut for Pakistan in a 1\u20130 win over [[Sri Lanka national football team|Sri Lanka]] in the [[South Asian Football Federation Gold Cup 2005|2005]] [[SAFF Championship|South Asian Football Federation Championship]] on 7 December 2005 at the [[Peoples Football Stadium]] in [[Karachi]].<ref name=\"footballpakistan3032\">{{cite news | last = Safi | first = Alam Zeb | title = Foreign coaches can lift football's graph: Zesh Rehman | publisher=Football Pakistan | date = 6 July 2008 | url = http://www.footballpakistan.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3032&Itemid=43 | accessdate =26 October 2008}}</ref> Rehman described his international debut as one of the best memories he has in football, adding, \"The reception I received from the first moment till the last was unforgettable. I felt loved, appreciated, respected and wanted and most of all the interest in football really grew immensely.\"<ref name=\"footballpakistan2563\">{{cite news | last = Naveed | first = Malik Riaz Hai | title = Exclusive Interview with Zesh Rehman | publisher=Football Pakistan | date = 17 October 2007 | url = http://www.footballpakistan.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2563&Itemid=43 | accessdate =26 October 2008}}</ref> Pakistan ultimately reached the semi-finals before losing out to [[Bangladesh national football team|Bangladesh]] 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news  | title = South Asian Gold Cup 2005 (Karachi, Pakistan) | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/saffgold05.html | accessdate =20 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nRehman was named in the Pakistan squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC first round|2010 World Cup qualifying]] matches against [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] in October 2007, and played the match in [[Lahore]] but could not help contain Asian champions Iraq from winning 7\u20130. In the second leg on 28 October he captained Pakistan to a 0\u20130 draw.<ref name=\"footballpakistan3032\"/> However, he also had to withdraw from the squad for the [[SAFF Championship 2008]] when he came down with [[food poisoning]].<ref name=\"pfa-summer\">{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Dave |title=After a disappointing summer, Zesh has high hopes for next season |publisher=[[Professional Footballers' Association]] |date=24 June 2008 |url=http://www.givemefootball.com/scottish-premier-league/after-a-disappointing-summer-zesh-has-high-hopes-f |accessdate=26 October 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> After nearly four years out, Rehman returned to the Pakistan team for the [[2012 AFC Challenge Cup qualification#Group B|2012 AFC Challenge Cup qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=AFC Challenge Cup 2012 Qualifiers: Know Your Rivals \u2013 India's Group B Opponents|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/3618/afc-challenge-cup-2012/2011/03/20/2402860/afc-challenge-cup-2012-qualifiers-know-your-rivals-indias|publisher=Goal|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013 Rehman represented Pakistan at the SAFF Championship which was held in Nepal. He played all of the games for Pakistan who narrowly missed out on a semi-final spot despite beating [[Bangladesh national football team|Bangladesh]] in the last group game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raheel |first=Natasha |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/600400/saff-championship-pakistan-crash-out-despite-beating-bangladesh/ |title=SAFF Championship: Pakistan crash out despite beating Bangladesh \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> His commanding displays during the tournament earned him a place in the Team of the Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goalnepal.com/news.php?id=16030 |title=SAFF Championship 2013: Team of the Tournament \u2013 Read & Comment |publisher=GoalNepal.com |date=12 September 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> In October 2013, Rehman captained Pakistan in both of their games at The Peace Cup held in the Philippines, and scored the winning goal in the opener against [[Chinese Taipei national football team|Chinese Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1049474/zesh-shines-as-pakistan-triumph-against-chinese-taipei |title=Zesh shines as Pakistan triumph against Chinese Taipei |publisher=Dawn.Com |date=14 October 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Raheel |first=Natasha |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/617647/pakistan-overcome-chinese-taipei-in-opener/ |title=Pakistan overcome Chinese Taipei in opener \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date=14 October 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\nRehman caused controversy in 2007 when in an interview with the British weekly newspaper the ''[[Eastern Eye (newspaper)|Eastern Eye]]'' he said that players of Asian descent should consider sticking to their roots rather than dreaming of playing for England. Rehman pointed to [[Michael Chopra]] and [[David Nugent]], who both were top scorer in the Championship, but Nugent was called up for [[England national football team|England]] while Chopra was not. Rehman claimed \"Why wasn't (Chopra) picked ahead of Dave Nugent? He's the top goal scorer in the Championship but he can't get in (the England set-up). So he needs to maybe look at his decision and go play for India instead of hanging on to the dream of playing for England, because it's not going to happen, end of discussion.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Chopra the wrong choice for India|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/sport-comment/chopra-the-wrong-choice-for-india#page2|publisher=The National|accessdate=2 June 2015|date=26 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRehman has said that, his \"sole purpose in trying to be a success as a professional footballer is to inspire other Asian players to follow my lead and achieve their goals.\"<ref name=\"pfa-role\">{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Dave |title=Zesh is a perfect role model \u2013 Captain of Pakistan, Rehman hopes to manage his country one day |publisher=[[Professional Footballers' Association]] |date=2 October 2008 |url=http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/pfa-news/zesh-is-a-perfect-role-model |accessdate=26 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007024229/http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/pfa-news/zesh-is-a-perfect-role-model |archivedate=7 October 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> He is an ambassador for the Asian Football Network (AFN), a grassroots community-led initiative designed to support and facilitate the development of grassroots Asian football in the UK.<ref>{{cite news | title = Zesh Rehman Partners | publisher=Zeshrehman.com | url = http://www.zeshrehman.com/partners.htm | accessdate =24 June 2009}}</ref> He has also worked with the [[Professional Footballers' Association]] (PFA) to try to increase the number of British Asians taking up a career in professional football, and has attended meetings with the PFA in order to achieve this goal.<ref name=\"pfa-about\">{{cite news|last=Pound |first=Simone |title=Players United Against Racism |publisher=[[Professional Footballers' Association]] |url=http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/about-the-pfa/pfa-and-anti-racism |accessdate=26 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928073951/http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa/about-the-pfa/pfa-and-anti-racism |archivedate=28 September 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> He has also been involved in the [[Show Racism the Red Card]] campaign and he has taken part in [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s \"Search for an Asian Star\" campaign.<ref name=\"people93463\"/> On 12 July 2008, he took part in the [[Islam Expo]] event at the [[Olympia, London|Olympia]] [[Convention center|exhibition centre]] in [[West Kensington, London|West Kensington]], London, a four-day event whose primary purpose was to build bridges between Britain's Muslim communities and the rest of society. Rehman took part in a panel giving feedback from his own experiences about the positive use of sport.<ref>{{cite news | title = F.A. Support Islam Expo Event 11\u201314&nbsp;July&nbsp;08 | publisher=Zesh Rehman's blog | date = 12 July 2008 | url = http://zeshrehman.blogspot.com/2008/07/islam-expo-at-london-olympia-11-14-july.html | accessdate =15 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Rehman appeared on the United States-based Afghan [[Satellite television|satellite]] television network [[Noor TV (US)|Noor TV]] and [[Bangladesh]]-based [[Islamic TV]] discussing being a Muslim footballer and how it is possible to pursue a career in football while sticking to Islamic roots. On 20 April 2008, he was a guest on the [[BBC Asian Network]] radio station show ''Breakdown'' revealing his favourite [[Desi]] music tunes.<ref>{{cite news | title = BBC Asian Network Schedule for 20&nbsp;April 2008 | publisher=[[BBC Asian Network]] | date = 20 April 2008 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/asiannetwork/programmes/schedules/2008/04/20 | accessdate =25 October 2008}}</ref> In May 2008, Rehman was awarded the ''Community Commitment Award'' at QPR.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former R's defender takes centre stage for charity|url=http://www.qprcommunitytrust.co.uk/news_article/135.aspx|publisher=QPR Community Trust|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=3 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706082605/http://www.qprcommunitytrust.co.uk/news_article/135.aspx|archive-date=6 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2008, Rehman took part in a radio documentary on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] about British Asians in football which followed his \"journey from playground to Premier League\".<ref name=\"Pak\"/>\n\nIn May 2010, he launched The Zesh Rehman Foundation at [[Valley Parade]] to encourage children from all backgrounds to participate in football and sport to better themselves.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Asian question |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,19689_6859510,00.html |work=Sky Sports |publisher=British Sky Broadcasting |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> He was named as one of the 50 World Cup Bid Ambassadors for The FA's World Cup 2018 bid, entered the Show Racism Red Card Hall of Fame,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.srtrc.org/about/hall-of-fame?page=6 |title=Hall of Fame |publisher=Show Racism the Red Card |accessdate=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724200725/http://www.srtrc.org/about/hall-of-fame?page=6 |archivedate=24 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and was invited onto the PFA management committee by Gordon Taylor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zeshrehman.com/partners.php |title=PFA Management Committee |publisher=Zeshrehman.com |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, he launched his [[iPhone]] [[iPhone application|application]] aimed at helping players who move overseas with the language barrier. He said that he thought of developing the application while his stint with [[Muangthong United]] as he had difficulty in communicating with his teammates.<ref name=\"MU\">{{cite web|title=The best manager I played for was Chris Coleman at Fulham, but Robbie Fowler will go onto be a top boss... he has great man-management skills|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2283382/The-Footballers-Football-Column--Zesh-Rehman-The-best-manager-I-played-Chris-Coleman-Fulham-Robbie-Fowler-boss.html|publisher=Daily Mail|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}}\n\nIn 2014, he was named as on the special [[Southeast Asia|South East Asia]] contributor for the ESPN South East Asia section by writing blogs and columns about football in the rapidly growing football region of Asia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.campaignasia.com/Article/390309,ESPN+launches+Southeast+Asia+edition+of+ESPN+FC.aspx|title=ESPN FC launches Southeast Asia edition of ESPN FC|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=16 December 2014|publisher=Campaign Asia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216170704/http://www.campaignasia.com/Article/390309,ESPN+launches+Southeast+Asia+edition+of+ESPN+FC.aspx|archive-date=16 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/football-asia/153/post/2052554/former-fulham-star-zesh-rehman-always-knew-asia-was-his-destiny|title=Former Fulham star Zesh Rehman: Asia was my destiny, Malaysia is my home|date=30 September 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014 |publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref> Rehman wrote his second blog for the ESPN South East Asia section a few days after his side recorded victory in the Malaysia Cup quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/football-asia/153/post/2086923/pahang-plan-to-win-malaysia-cup-semifinal-to-celebrate-kings-birthday|title=Pahang plan to win Malaysia Cup semi to celebrate King's birthday|date=15 October 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014 | last = Rehman| first = Zesh |publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club statistics===\n{{updated|match played on 14 June 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n