{"title_page": "Death of Kelly Thomas", "text_new": "{{Infobox News event\n|image_name  = Kelly Thomas American.jpg\n|caption     = Kelly Thomas in 2002<ref>{{cite web |author=Lauren Lloyd |url=http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |title=Over 14K People Want Fullerton Police Officers Fired for Murder of Kelly Thomas |publisher=LAist |date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018231753/http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |archivedate=October 18, 2015 }}</ref>\n|date        = {{start date|2011|07|05}}\n|time        = 8:30 PM [[Pacific Standard Time|PDT]] (03:30 UTC)\n|place       = [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], [[California]], United States\n|participants = [[Fullerton Police Department]] officers Manuel Ramos, Jay Cicinelli, and Joseph Wolfe\n|charges = [[Second-degree murder]] (Class A Felony) (Manuel Ramos)<br>[[Involuntary manslaughter]] (Class A Felony) (Ramos, Jay Cicinelli, Joseph Wolfe)<br>Excessive force (Cicinelli, Wolfe)\n|verdict = Not guilty of all charges (Ramos, Cicinelli)<br>No verdict for Wolfe (charges were dropped)\n}}\n'''Kelly Thomas''' (April 5, 1974 \u2013 July 10, 2011) was a homeless man diagnosed with [[schizophrenia]] who lived on the streets of [[Fullerton, California]]. He was beaten to death by six members of the [[Fullerton Police Department]], on July 5, 2011.<ref name=\"Wolfedrop\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/kelly-thomas-fullerton-police-officers-beating-trial-joseph-wolfe-charges-dropped/1972899/|title=Third Ex-Fullerton Police Officer Won\u2019t Face Charges in Kelly Thomas Death}}</ref> Thomas was taken to [[St. Jude Medical Center]] before being transferred to the [[UC Irvine Medical Center]], where he was comatose on arrival and not expected to recover. He never regained consciousness, and died on July 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fatal Fullerton police beating of homeless man sparks outcry |first=Abby |last=Sewell |first2=Kate |last2=Mather |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/08/fatal-fullerton-police-beating-of-homeless-man-sparks-outcry.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 2, 2011}}</ref><ref name=timeline>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Timeline-The-Kelly-Thomas-Case-in-Fullerton-126851443.html |title=Timeline: The Kelly Thomas Case |last1=Lloyd |first1=Jonathan |date=Jan 13, 2014 |publisher=[[NBC Southern California]] |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nMedical records show that bones in his face were broken and he choked on his own blood.<ref>{{cite web|author=Amy Taxin & Greg Risling |url=https://news.yahoo.com/apnewsbreak-ca-police-officer-charged-murder-175213929.html |title=APNewsBreak: CA police officer charged with murder |publisher=Yahoo News |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> The coroner concluded that compression of the [[thorax]] made it impossible for Thomas to breathe normally and deprived his brain of oxygen.<ref name=Christine21 /> His parents removed him from life support five days later, and he died from his injuries on July 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Denisse Salazar |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/officers-307824-thomas-goodrich.html |title=Man who scuffled with police dies |publisher=OC Register |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Officer Manuel Ramos was charged with one count of [[Murder (United States law)#Degrees of murder in the United States|second-degree murder]] and one count of [[involuntary manslaughter]]; Corporal Jay Cicinelli and Officer Joseph Wolfe were each charged with one count of felony involuntary manslaughter and one count of [[excessive force]].<ref name=Christine21>{{cite news |title=2 police officers charged in death of Calif man |first=Christina |last=Ng |last2=Risling |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/kelly-thomas-police-officers-charged-beating-death-homeless/story?id=14575028 |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Ian Lovett |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/us/california-police-charged-in-killing.html?scp=4&sq=%22kelly%20thomas%22&st=cse |title=California: Police Charged in Killing |work=[[New York Times]] |date=September 22, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Grand jury: Third Fullerton officer beat Kelly Thomas |author=Nicole Santa Cruz |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/10/grand-jury-testimony-says-third-officer-used-excessive-force-.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=October 11, 2012 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> All three pleaded not guilty.\n\nA judge declined to dismiss the charges against the officers in January 2013, finding that \"a reasonable person could infer that the use of force was excessive and unreasonable.\"<ref name=\"dismiss1\">{{cite news |title=Judge Turns Down Dismissal Request in Kelly Thomas Case |author=Tracy Wood |url=http://www.voiceofoc.org/countywide/this_just_in/article_9649b5c8-5c70-11e2-9dfa-001a4bcf887a.html |newspaper=Voice of OC |date=January 11, 2012 |accessdate=January 11, 2012}}</ref> An appeals court judge also denied a request to overturn the lower court's decision.<ref name=\"dismiss2\">{{cite news|title=Court won't toss charges against ex-cop in Kelly Thomas death |author=Abby Sewell |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2013/03/kelly-thomas-officer-appeal-denied.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref> On January 13, 2014, Ramos and Cicinelli were found not guilty of all charges,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lopez |first=Andrew |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Former-Fullerton-Officers-Manuel-Ramos-Found-by-Jury-in-Kelly-Thomas-Trial-239924741.html?_osource=SocialFlowFB_LABrand |title=Jury Finds Ex-Officers Accused in Kelly Thomas Death Not Guilty &#124; NBC Southern California |publisher=Nbclosangeles.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> while the trial for Wolfe was pending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ktla.com/2014/01/13/verdict-reached-in-trial-of-ex-officers-in-kelly-thomas-death |title=Ex-Officers Found Not Guilty in Kelly Thomas\u2019 Beating Death &#124; KTLA 5 |publisher=Ktla.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> Following the verdict for the two officers, the district attorney's office announced it would not pursue the case against Wolfe.<ref>{{cite news\n | last1 = Flores   | first1 = Adolfo\n | last2 = Esquivel | first2 = Paloma\n | url = https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-live-verdict-in-kelly-thomas-police-murder-case-20140113,0,5661959.story\n | title = Police not guilty in Kelly Thomas death; DA won't try 3rd officer\n | work = Los Angeles Times\n | date = January 13, 2014\n | access-date = September 14, 2014\n}}</ref> On January 17, 2014, charges against Wolfe were dropped.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Kelly Thomas 2009 booking photo released by Fullerton PD.jpg|thumb|Kelly Thomas as he appeared in a 2009 booking photo released by Fullerton PD]]\nKelly Thomas was born April 5, 1974, to Ron Thomas, a former [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] Sheriff's deputy,<ref>{{cite web |last=Lopez |first=Steve |title=Kelly Thomas' father fights for justice |date=August 6, 2011 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/06/local/la-me-0807-lopez-kellythomas-20110805 |accessdate=September 22, 2011}}</ref> and Cathy Thomas.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-fullerton-death-pictures,0,3009403.photogallery?index=la-me004_homeless.5.gmf|title= Homeless man dies after run-in with Fullerton police|first= Gina |last=Ferazzi|date= August 2, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Thomas, who was diagnosed with schizophrenia, was a \"fixture\" among Fullerton's homeless population.<ref>{{cite news |title=Embattled Fullerton police chief goes on medical leave |first=Abby |last=Sewell |first2=Richard |last2=Winton |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-fullerton-death-20110811,0,6106396.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> The death of Thomas has sparked debate about systemic reforms in treatment of the mentally ill.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/08/local/la-me-kelly-thomas-mental-20120509 |title=Kelly Thomas video a turning point for mental health care? |author=Scott Gold, Richard Winton and Abby Sewell |date=May 8, 2012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1990 and 2011, Thomas had 92 encounters with the police. These encounters ranged from minor infractions such as trespassing to a guilty plea in an assault with a deadly weapon case sixteen years prior.<ref name=ocr20121018>{{cite news|title=Kelly Thomas: 92 police encounters since 1990|url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-374958-police-attorney.html|accessdate=October 18, 2012|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=October 18, 2012|author=Irving, Doug|author2=Ponsi, Lou}}</ref><ref name=abc />\n\n==Incident==\n[[File:Kelly-Thomas-pool-of-blood-crime-scene-exhibit-photo.jpg|thumb|right|The crime scene in the immediate aftermath of the beating]]\n\n[[File:Kelly-Thomas-Police-Beating.jpg|thumb|Kelly Thomas, after the attack from the officers of the Fullerton, California Police Department]]\nOn July 5, 2011, at about 8:30 PM, officers of the Fullerton Police Department responded to a call from the management of the Slidebar<ref name=\"slidebar\" /> that someone was vandalizing cars near the [[Fullerton (train station)|Fullerton Transportation Center]]. While investigating, they encountered the shirtless and disheveled Thomas and attempted to search him. According to statements given by the officers, Thomas was uncooperative and resisted when they attempted to search him, so backup was called.<ref name=\"LATimesEarly\">{{cite web|author=Kate Mather and Abby Sewell |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0803-fullerton-death-20110803,0,4180513.story |title=Fullerton police beating of homeless man is under investigation |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 2, 2011 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> \"Now you see my fists?\" Fullerton police officer Manuel Ramos asked Thomas while slipping on a pair of latex gloves. \"Yeah, what about them?\" Thomas responded. \"They are getting ready to fuck you up,\" said Ramos, to which Thomas replied, \"Start punching, dude\". A video of the event surfaced. Thomas can be seen being uncooperative with the officers, but sitting and being non-aggressive. After the officers grab Thomas to arrest him for stolen mail they apparently found, Thomas can be heard repeatedly screaming in pain while officers are heard repeatedly asking him to place his arms behind his back. He audibly responds \"Okay, I'm sorry!\" and \"I'm trying!\" while the officers stretch his arm back. The police officers claim that, unable to get Thomas to comply with the requests, they used a [[taser]] on him (up to five times according to a witness statement, and the video footage), and in the video Thomas can be heard screaming for his father.<ref name=\"LATimesEarly\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=friendsforfullerton |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ljYNgLnpxM |title=Police Beating of Kelly Thomas in Fullerton, CA |publisher=YouTube |date=July 23, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Six officers were involved in subduing Thomas, who was unarmed and had a history of mental illness. Thomas was initially taken to St. Jude Medical Center in Fullerton but was transferred immediately to the [[UC Irvine Medical Center]] with severe injuries to his head, face, and neck.<ref>{{cite web|author=Eliza Fisher |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/27/police-beat-homeless-full_n_911419.html |title=Police Beat Homeless Fullerton Man Kelly Thomas To Death |publisher=Huffington Post |date=July 27, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> One of the paramedics testified that he was first instructed to attend to a police officer's minor injury and then noticed Thomas lying unconscious in a pool of blood.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?id=9349329| author=Eileen Frere| title=Kelly Thomas trial: Forensic expert, paramedic testify| publisher=ABC News| date=December 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/officers-acquitted-in-death-of-kelly-thomas/2014/01/14/3e660b24-7d24-11e3-95c6-0a7aa80874bc_story.html |title=Officers acquitted in death of Kelly Thomas |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref>\n\nOrange County District Attorney [[Tony Rackauckas]] gave a detailed account of the events during a press conference on September 21, 2011. Using digital audio recording devices carried by the officers, surveillance video from a pole camera<ref>{{YouTube|KU0Imk2Bstg|surveillance video from a pole camera}}</ref> at the Fullerton Transportation Center, and other evidence, Rackauckas provided evidence that Thomas did comply with orders from Ramos, who had put on latex gloves and asked Thomas \"Now see my fists? They are getting ready to fuck you up.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Welsh |url=http://documents.latimes.com/charges-kelly-thomas-police/ |title=Charges against police in homeless man\u2019s death |work=LA Times |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Rackauckas went on to describe how Thomas begged for his life, before being struck repeatedly by the officers. He was admitted to the hospital, slipped into a coma, and died five days later.<ref>{{cite web|author=Abby Sewell and Richard Winton |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/09/kelly-thomas-begged-for-his-life-from-menacing-officer-da-says.html |title=Kelly Thomas begged for his life from 'menacing' officer, D.A. says |work=LA Times |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe story of his beating broke shortly before his death.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sean Emery |url=http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-07-06/news/29748743_1_goodrich-life-threatening-injuries-officers |title=Man who scuffled with police still in critical condition |publisher=OC Register |date=July 6, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715202530/http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-07-06/news/29748743_1_goodrich-life-threatening-injuries-officers |archivedate=July 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sam Quinones |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/07/homeless-man-dies-5-days-after-fight-with-fullerton-police-.html |title=Homeless man dies 5 days after fight with Fullerton police |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> An investigation into the beating was undertaken by the Orange County district attorney starting on July 7, 2011,<ref name=Ponsi4>{{cite news |title=ACLU: D.A. should not investigate fatal police fight |first=Lou |last=Ponsi |url=http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-08-04/news/29856409_1_police-officers-investigation-aclu |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130202213/http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-08-04/news/29856409_1_police-officers-investigation-aclu |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |newspaper=The Orange County Register |date=August 4, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 }}</ref> and later the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] became involved.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/orange_county&id=8279826 |title=FBI investigating Fullerton police beating |publisher=KABC-TV Los Angeles |date=July 30, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> The decision to involve the FBI was praised by the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], which claims the Orange County district attorney has an \"abysmal\" record when investigating shootings with police involvement.<ref name=Ponsi4 />\n\nKelly Thomas was removed from life support and died on July 10, 2011, five days after the beating.<ref name=abc>{{cite web|author= |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/orange_county&id=8243047 |title=Family says beaten man at hands of Fullerton police taken off life support |publisher=KABC-TV Los Angeles |date=July 10, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Initial reports claimed that Thomas had been very combative with officers and two had suffered broken bones.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/orange_county&id=8244594 |title=Family seeks witnesses to Fullerton police beating |publisher=KABC-TV Los Angeles |date=July 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Later, the police department confirmed that no officers had suffered any broken bones, and that no one other than Thomas had any significant injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alex Stouffer |url=http://fullertonian.com/Blogs/tabid/97/ArticleType/ArticleView/ArticleID/408/Default.aspx |title=Protests & The Investigation of Kelly Thomas\u2019s Death |publisher=Fullertonian |date=July 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> By the end of July, several news outlets had picked up the story and it had become international news.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Quigley |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2019225/Kelly-Thomas-Police-beat-taser-gentle-mentally-ill-homeless-man-death.html |title=Caught on tape: Police beat and taser 'gentle' mentally-ill homeless man to death |work=Daily Mail |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2011, a large protest outside the Fullerton Police Department was organized by several people, including the victim's father Ron Thomas.<ref>{{cite web|author=E.D. Kain |url=https://blogs.forbes.com/erikkain/2011/07/30/protests-investigation-follow-police-beating-of-kelly-thomas/ |title=Protests, Investigation Follow Police Beating of Kelly Thomas |publisher=Forbes.com |date=July 30, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Fullerton City Council.jpg|thumb|Ron Thomas speaks to the Fullerton City Council and the media]]\nOn August 2, 2011 many members of the public spoke out about the beating at the biweekly city council meeting at the Fullerton City Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fullerton.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=2&clip_id=295 |archive-date=December 8, 2011|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20111208121027/http://fullerton.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id%3D2%26clip_id%3D295 |url-status=dead|title=City Council/Redevelopment Agency Regular Meeting |publisher=City of Fullerton, California |date=August 2, 2011 |accessdate=August 7, 2011 }}</ref> Over 70 members of the public spoke to the city council, the vast majority of whom criticized the police. Among the speakers was Ron Thomas, the father of Kelly Thomas, as well as Kelly Thomas's stepmother. The public comment session lasted for approximately three hours. The city attorney emphasized that the city council could not respond to the comments, however following the public comment period discussion was given to provide clarification on the city's policy regarding the mentally ill. In addition, Tony Bushala, a local developer and conservative activist, announced plans to recall three members of the city council thought to have responded insufficiently to the beating.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ian Lovett |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/04/us/04homeless.html |title=Death of Homeless Man After Beating by Police Stirs Outrage |work=The New York Times |date=August 3, 2011 |accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> The recall qualified on the ballot in February 2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/02/fullerton-recall.html |title=Recall election OKd for three Fullerton City Council members |author=Abby Sewell |date= February 6, 2012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> with a recall election scheduled for Don Bankhead, F. Dick Jones, and Pat McKinley on June 5, 2012, consolidated with the statewide primary election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityoffullerton.com/depts/city_clerk/elections/june_election/default.asp |title=Special Recall Election |author=City of Fullerton |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> On June 5, 2012 all three council members were successfully recalled by Fullerton residents.<ref>{{cite web|author=Abby Sewell |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/07/local/la-me-0607-fullerton-20120607-1 |title=Successful Fullerton City Council recall paves way for change |work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 7, 2012 |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday August 6, 2011, a large street protest was held outside of the Fullerton City Hall. Activists at that protest, which was attended by hundreds of people, called for the release of a surveillance video shot by cameras installed at the bus depot and carried signs with slogans like \"Jail All Killer Cops\" and \"End Police Brutality.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Winton and Abby Sewell |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-fullerton-death-20110807,0,6368545.story |title=Hundreds protest Fullerton man's death, call for release of video |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=August 6, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn late September 2011, the officers involved were arrested on murder charges. Local law enforcement personnel showed support by raising money for their bail and criminal defense.<ref>\"Friends of Fullerton's Future website, retrieved May 9, 2012</ref>\n\nThirty days after the incident all six officers involved in the beating were placed on [[administrative leave]] with pay and benefits intact. Several people, including two members of the Fullerton City Council, called for the resignation of police Chief Michael Sellers,<ref>{{cite web|author=Abby Sewell and Richard Winton |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0804-fullerton-death-20110804,0,5949987.story |title=Fullerton police draw fire for silence in homeless man's death |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 4, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> who was later placed on medical leave in August 2011 for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/11/local/la-me-fullerton-death-20110811 |title=Embattled Fullerton police chief goes on medical leave |author=Abby Sewell and Richard Winton |date=August 11, 2011 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Sellers continued his medical leave for 7 months and resigned on February 18, 2012 having never returned to work.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/sellers-338806-chief-city.html |title=Beleaguered Fullerton police chief to retire |publisher=Orange County Register |date=Aug 21, 2013 |author=Michael Mello |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> 19,948 people have signed an online petition calling for the firing of all six police officers that were present during the beating.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |title=Over 14K People Want Fullerton Police Officers Fired for Murder of Kelly Thomas |author=Lauren Lloyd |date=October 24, 2011 |publisher=LAist |accessdate=October 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018231753/http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |archivedate=October 18, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFullerton City Councilman Bruce Whitaker later went on television stating his belief that there was a cover-up of the beating of Thomas within the police department and that the six officers involved in the beating falsified their reports on the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://voiceofoc.org/oc_north/article_6ca7dad0-fac2-11e0-a80e-001cc4c002e0.html |title=Councilman Alleges Cover-Up in Kelly Thomas Police Beating |author=Nick Gerda |date=October 25, 2011 |work= |publisher=Voice of OC |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA preliminary hearing to determine if there is sufficient evidence for a trial was held on May 9, 2012. The court ordered that two of the police officers involved will stand trial. Manuel Ramos was charged with second-degree murder and involuntary manslaughter, and Jay Cicinelli was charged with involuntary manslaughter and felony use of excessive force. Both officers pleaded not guilty at the second arraignment on July 13, 2012.<ref name=ocr20120714>{{cite news|last=Welborn|first=Larry|title=Officers plead not guilty in death of Kelly Thomas|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=July 14, 2012|pages=Local 1, 3}}</ref> Attempts by the defendants to dismiss the charges were denied.<ref name=\"dismiss1\" /><ref name=\"dismiss2\" /> In September 2012, Officer Joseph Wolfe was indicted on charges of involuntary manslaughter and use of excessive force.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/27/joseph-wolfe-kelly-thomas_n_1921322.html |title=Joseph Wolfe Arrested In Kelly Thomas Beating Death: Third Fullerton Police Officer Charged |author=Amy Taxin |date=September 27, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2013 |publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2012, press reports indicated that the Fullerton City Council had agreed to pay Thomas' mother one million dollars as a settlement of her civil complaints against the city. This did not impact the ongoing civil actions by Thomas' father or the criminal trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/16/local/la-me-0516-kelly-thomas-settlement-20120516 |title=Homeless man's mother settles with Fullerton over his death |author=Richard Winton |date=16 May 2012|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nTrials for Cicinelli and Ramos were scheduled to begin October 18, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2013/07/05/38055/kelly-thomas-beating-two-years-later-ex-fullerton/|title=Kelly Thomas beating: 2 years later, ex-Fullerton police officers face trial|first=Ed|last=Joyce|date=July 5, 2013|publisher=Southern California Public Radio}}</ref> but actually began on December 2, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Welborn|first=Larry|title=D.A.: Officer fueled routine meeting into Thomas death|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/thomas-539675-ramos-officers.html|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=The Orange County Register|date=December 2, 2013|author2=Jolly, Vik}}</ref> Proceedings concluded on January 13, 2014 with both Ramos and Cicinelli being found not guilty of any criminal charges.<ref name=verdict>{{cite web|last=Pamer|first=Melissa|title=Ex-Officers Found Not Guilty in Kelly Thomas\u2019 Beating Death |url=http://ktla.com/2014/01/13/verdict-reached-in-trial-of-ex-officers-in-kelly-thomas-death/#axzz2qKOGQwjZ|accessdate=14 January 2014|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> After the verdicts, the District Attorney's office announced that it would not proceed with Wolfe's trial.\n\nThe protests picked up again after the acquittals. On January 18, 2014, 14 people were arrested for protesting after ignoring a dispersal order from the police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-kelly-thomas-protest-update-20140118-story.html|title=At least 10 protesters arrested at Fullerton rally for Kelly Thomas|date=January 19, 2014|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 2017, federal prosecutors announced that they would not bring charges against former officers Ramos, Cicinelli and Wolfe for violating Thomas' civil rights.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ocregister.com/2017/01/24/kelly-thomas-case-5-years-later-feds-say-no-criminal-charges-against-fullerton-police-officers/| author=Sean Emery| title=Kelly Thomas case: 5 years later, feds say no criminal charges against Fullerton police officers| publisher=The Orange County Register| date=January 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Slidebar Kitchen involvement===\nIn June 2012 Michael Reeves, a former employee of the Slidebar Rock-N-Roll Kitchen, filed a lawsuit for wrongful termination against Jeremy Popoff related to the beating.<ref name=\"reeve2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/thomas-358499-police-reeves.html |title=Suit: False report sent police to Kelly Thomas |first1=Doug|last1=Irving|first2=Lou|last2= Ponsi |date=Jun 13, 2012 |work=OC Register |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/kelly-thomas-ron-thomas-jeremy-popoff-slidebar-fullerton-michael-reeves-jeanette-demarco-lawsuit-homeless-158691165.html |title=$16M Lawsuit Claims Restaurant Falsely Reported Kelly Thomas to Police |author=Caroline Tan and Vikki Vargas |date=Jun 13, 2012 |work= |publisher=NBC-LA |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> The Slidebar, which is owned by Popoff, the guitarist for [[Lit (band)|Lit]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2012/06/12/fullerton-bar-owner-denies-false-report-led-to-homeless-mans-death/|title=Fullerton Bar Owner Denies False Report Led To Homeless Man's Death|date=June 12, 2012}}</ref> was the source of the call that caused police to report to the area and confront Thomas.<ref name=\"slidebar\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2011/08/slidebar_kelly_thomas_call_police.php |title=&#91;UPDATE: Thomas' Previous Slidebar Encounters&#93; Sources: Slidebar Kitchen Placed Call Resulting in Kelly Thomas' Death |author=Brandon Ferguson |date=Aug 23, 2011 |work= |publisher=OC Weekly |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Reeves, a bouncer at the establishment, made statements to investigators claiming the Slidebar had a policy to do \"anything necessary\" to keep loiterers out of the area and that his manager lied about Thomas breaking into cars when calling the police to get them to respond more quickly.<ref name=\"reeve\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/13/kelly-thomas-beating-death-lawsuit-false-police-report-slidebar_n_1594253.html |title=Kelly Thomas Beating: Lawsuit Alleges Slidebar's 'False' Police Report Led To Thomas' Death |author=Anna Almendrala |date=June 6, 2012 |work= |publisher=Huffington Post |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> He further claims that Thomas was only loitering in the area that night and not causing trouble. Soon after making statements to investigators about what he saw that night he claims his managers were \"furious at him for it\" and slowly started taking away his responsibilities, culminating with his firing two months later.<ref name=\"reeve\" /> Reeves also claims that Popoff wanted everyone working at the Slidebar to act as if the \"Slidebar had nothing to do\" with the beating of Thomas and his refusal to echo these statements is the chief reason why he was fired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2012/06/slidebar_jeremy_popoff_lawsuit.php |title=Lawsuit: Fullerton Bar Manager Enticed Police with a Lie Before Officers Beat Kelly Thomas to Death |author=R. Scott Moxley |date= June 12, 2012 |work= |publisher=OC Weekly |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Eric Dubin, an attorney representing the Slidebar and Popoff, claims the suit is without merit and that it should be quickly dismissed. Dubin claims that \"This whole thing is all copy from blogs and sold to some lawyer\" and that, while the call did originate from the Slidebar, \"that she [the manager] never used the phrase 'breaking into cars.'\" Dubin further claims that \"Everything in that lawsuit is 100 percent false\"<ref name=\"reeve\" /> and the real reason Reeve was fired was because of a confrontation with a manager in front of customers.<ref name=\"reeve2\" /> On June 12, 2012, Ron Thomas organized a small gathering outside of the Slidebar to protest the false police report.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fullertonstories.com/lawsuit-highlights-call-to-police-in-kelly-thomas-case/ |title=Lawsuit Highlights Call To Police in Kelly Thomas Case |author= |date=June 12, 2012 |work= |publisher=Fullerton Stories |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Thomas and Popoff talked during the event and Thomas later said that if the report was correct, \"then I have no beef\" but that if there are any inconsistencies then \"I have to do what I have to do\".\n\nOne day after this statement, on June 13, 2012, after months of denials, Slidebar owner Jeremy Popoff stated on [[KFI]]'s [[John and Ken|John and Ken Show]] that one of his employees did, in fact, call police the night Kelly Thomas was beaten. He declined to say what the employee reported, citing the criminal investigation into Thomas' death, but said a recording of the call has been reviewed by the District Attorney's Office and other investigators.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-358721-officers-slidebar.html |title=Bouncer: I knew Kelly Thomas report was false |author=Doug Irving |date=June 13, 2012 |work= |publisher=Orange County Register |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Popoff and his lawyer denied the claims of an anti-homeless policy during a press conference.\n\nThe issue was eventually solved in a settlement.<ref>Ponsi, Lou. [http://www.ocregister.com/articles/reeves-519774-slidebar-thomas.html \"Ex-bouncer's Lawsuit in Kelly Thomas Death Settled.\"] The Orange County Register. The OC Register, 5 August 2013. Retrieved 15 December 2014.</ref> This sparked renewed protests in front of the Slidebar Kitchen.\n\n===Cause of death===\nOn September 21, 2011, Orange County district attorney [[Tony Rackauckas]] held a press conference to announce the results of the investigation. Rackauckas announced that according to the Orange County coroner, the cause of death was \"[[asphyxia]] caused by mechanical chest compression with blunt cranial-facial injuries sustained during physical altercation with law enforcement.\" Rackauckas said Thomas died because of the force of the officers on his chest, which made it impossible for him to breathe, causing Thomas to become unconscious. He then became comatose, and died when taken off life support five days later.\n\nAccording to Rackauckas, the coroner stated that the injuries to Thomas' face and head contributed to his death. Also contributing to his death were brain injuries, facial and rib fractures, and the extensive bruising and abrasions he suffered during the beating, which left him lying in a \"growing pool of blood\", Rackauckas said. The toxicology report shows that Thomas had no illicit drugs or alcohol in his system.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alyssa Newcomb |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/kelly-thomas-beating-video-fullerton-officers-court/story?id=16302273#.T-9VYEMy7dX |title=California Judge to Decide Whether Cops Will Stand Trial for Beating Homeless Man |publisher=ABC |date=May 8, 2012 |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Thomas was severely bleeding and struggled and pleaded, \"I can't breathe,\" \"Dad, help me.\" The DA stated that the officers did not reduce their level of force during the nearly 10-minute assault.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-318320-death-rackauckas.html?nstrack=sid:2589472%7Cmet:102%7Ccat:227%7Corder:1 |title=Kelly Thomas died of asphyxia, report says |author=Denisse Salazar |date=September 21, 2011 |work= |publisher=Voice of OC |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, Dr. Gary Vilke (a professor of clinical emergency medicine at UC San Diego) testified for the defense during the trial. He has investigated in-custody deaths for 20 years and has published studies on \"mechanical compression.\"<ref name=\"KPCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/01/09/41476/kelly-thomas-trial-da-makes-final-appeal-jurors-be/ |title=Kelly Thomas Trial: DA makes final appeal, jurors begin deliberations (updated) &#124; 89.3 KPCC |publisher=Scpr.org |date=2014-01-09 |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref> He testified, \u201cI know he was breathing when the officers got off him because he was still talking.\"  \"As far as the cause of death, it\u2019s not asphyxiation.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|last=Flores |first=Adolfo |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-kelly-thomas-did-not-die-of-asphyxiation-witness-says-20131216,0,3491049.story#ixzz2qhqqOuZu |title=Kelly Thomas did not die of asphyxiation, expert witness testifies |publisher=latimes.com |date=2013-12-16 |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref> The defense also implied medical treatment could have played a part in Thomas's death (hospital records reportedly showed that a tube placed down his windpipe to assist his breathing had been pushed too far).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kabc.com/common/page.php?pt=Prosecution+Takes+a+Beating+in+the+Kelly+Thomas+Trial&id=22553&is_corp=0 |title=Prosecution Takes a Beating in the Kelly Thomas Trial |publisher=[[KABC (AM)]] |accessdate=2014-01-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224857/http://www.kabc.com/common/page.php?pt=Prosecution+Takes+a+Beating+in+the+Kelly+Thomas+Trial&id=22553&is_corp=0 |archivedate=2014-02-01 }}</ref> The prosecution dismissed these claims, saying they did not apply and their value was not great enough.<ref name=\"KPCC\"/>\n\n===Lawsuit by father===\nWithin days after the incident, Ron Thomas, the father of Kelly Thomas, retained noted personal injury and civil rights attorney [[Garo Mardirossian]] to represent him in a civil action against the City of Fullerton and the involved officers. Mr. Mardirossian then held several press conferences to address bringing criminal charges against Officer Manuel Ramos, Corporal Jay Cicinelli, and Officer Joseph Wolfe, and the civil lawsuit filed against the City. These press conferences aired locally, nationally, and internationally heightening public interest, and imposing pressure on the Orange County District Attorney to file criminal charges.\n\nIn the civil proceedings, Cathy Thomas, the mother of Kelly Thomas, settled for $1 million. Cathy Thomas was represented by another lawyer.\n\nDespite the subsequent not guilty verdicts in favor of Officer Ramos and Corporal Cicinelli, Mr. Mardirossian obtained a $4.9 million settlement just before Manuel Ramos, the chief perpetrator, was to testify in the civil jury trial. The settlement precluded the officers who were fired from being re-hired by Fullerton Police Department.\n\n===Criminal trial===\nOn January 13, 2014, Manuel Ramos was acquitted of second-degree murder and involuntary manslaughter in the 2011 death of Thomas. Jay Cicinelli was acquitted of involuntary manslaughter and excessive use of force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2014/01/14/kelly-thomas-trial-officers-acquitted-in-homeless-man-death/ |title=Kelly Thomas trial: Officers acquitted in homeless man's death |author=Associated Press |date=January 14, 2014 |work= |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=January 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Recall election===\nIn a landslide June 5, 2012 recall election, city council members Dick Jones, Don Bankhead and Pat McKinley were voted out of office. Each was voted out by an almost identical majority of nearly 66%. Their replacements were: Travis Kiger, a planning commissioner and blogger for the site Friends for Fullerton's Future, who filled Jones' term, which expired December 4, 2012; Greg Sebourn, a land surveyor, who filled Bankhead's term, which also ended December 4; and attorney Doug Chaffee, who filled McKinley's term, which ended December 2, 2012. All were sworn into office in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/07/local/la-me-0607-fullerton-20120607-1 |title=Successful Fullerton City Council recall paves way for change |author= Abby Sewell |date=June 7, 2012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> Tony Bushala, a leading organizer of the Fullerton recall election, said he was seeking accountability for Kelly Thomas' death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2012-06-06/us/us_california-fullerton-recall-election_1_involuntary-manslaughter-election-officials-homeless-man?_s=PM:US |title=3 California councilmen ousted in recall over alleged police brutality |author=Michael Martinez and Casey Wian |date=June 6, 2012 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=July 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619223600/http://articles.cnn.com/2012-06-06/us/us_california-fullerton-recall-election_1_involuntary-manslaughter-election-officials-homeless-man?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=June 19, 2012 }}</ref> The city's other two council members did not face a recall.\n\n===Employment termination===\nOn July 3, 2012, Ramos' employment was terminated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sewell|first=Abby |title=Officer charged in Kelly Thomas' death leaves police force |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/07/fullerton-officer-no-longer-employed.html |accessdate=July 11, 2012 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\nAccording to a statement issued by Fullerton Police, Joe Wolfe is no longer employed by the department as of July 16, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Kelly-Thomas-Manuel-Ramos-Jay-Cicinelli-Officer-Joe-Wolfe-Fullerton-Police-Department-162824596.html |title=Two Officers Involved in Kelly Thomas Beating No Longer Work for City: Police |first=Samantha|last= Tata |date=July 17, 2012 |publisher=NBC Southern California}}</ref>\nJay Cicinelli is no longer employed by Fullerton Police as of July 20, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-364830-officers-cicinelli.html |title=Kelly Thomas case: Third officer no longer employed |publisher=ocregister.com |date=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Anonymous response===\n\nIn August 2011, the Internet activist group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] demanded that the officers involved be prosecuted, the Fullerton Police Chief resign, and that Thomas's family be awarded US$5 million in compensation; they threatened to shut down the Fullerton municipal website if their demands were not met.<ref name=\"Almendrala2011\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/15/kelly-thomas-anonymous_n_927305.html|accessdate=2014-07-21|date=2011-10-15|first=Anna|last=Almendrala|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|title=Kelly Thomas Death Spurs 'Anonymous' Hackers To Action|publisher=[[AOL]]|archivedate=2014-02-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203011820/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/15/kelly-thomas-anonymous_n_927305.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2014, after the police officers involved were acquitted, Anonymous [[doxing|released their personal addresses]],<ref name=\"King2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/personal-info-of-cops-in-kelly-thomas-case-released-by-anonymous/article/366599|title=Personal info of cops in Kelly Thomas case released by Anonymous|last=King|first=Justin|date=2014-01-19|newspaper=Digital Journal|archivedate=2014-02-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203021315/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/personal-info-of-cops-in-kelly-thomas-case-released-by-anonymous/article/366599|url-status=live|accessdate=2014-07-21}}</ref> as well as the identities of the jurors.<ref name=\"Murphy2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/news/anonymous-opfullerton-kelly-thomas/|title=Anonymous's #OpFullerton seeks justice for Kelly Thomas|last=Murphy|first=Lorraine|date=2014-01-24|accessdate=2014-07-21|newspaper=[[The Daily Dot]]|archivedate=2014-04-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403151337/http://www.dailydot.com/news/anonymous-opfullerton-kelly-thomas/|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 18 and 19, Anonymous took down several websites belonging to or run by Fullerton police and municipality.<ref name=\"Murphy2014\"/><ref name=\"Amir2014\">{{cite news|url=http://hackread.com/anonymous-takes-down-fullerton-police-website-against-arrest/|title=#OpFullerton: Anonymous takes down Fullerton police website against protesters arrest and Kelly Thomas tribute|last=Amir|first=Waqas|date=2014-01-19|archivedate=2014-03-13|accessdate=2014-07-21|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313105824/http://hackread.com/anonymous-takes-down-fullerton-police-website-against-arrest/|work=HackRead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of killings by law enforcement officers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160419011555/http://fullertonfactcheck.com/kelly-thomas-a-quiet-gentle-soul/ ''Fullerton Stories'' has a brief write up about Thomas' life]\n*[http://www.fullertonsfuture.org/tag/kelly-thomas-beating/ ''Friends For Fullerton'', a blog with extensive coverage of the event]\n*{{YouTube|KU0Imk2Bstg|Security footage of the beating}}\n\n{{Fullerton, California}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Kelly}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Criminal trials that ended in acquittal]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths in police custody in the United States]]\n[[Category:Homeless people]]\n[[Category:People from Fullerton, California]]\n[[Category:History of Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:People with schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Victims of police brutality]]\n[[Category:2011 in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Filmed killings by law enforcement]]wtf\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox News event\n|image_name  = Kelly Thomas American.jpg\n|caption     = Kelly Thomas in 2002<ref>{{cite web |author=Lauren Lloyd |url=http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |title=Over 14K People Want Fullerton Police Officers Fired for Murder of Kelly Thomas |publisher=LAist |date=October 24, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018231753/http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |archivedate=October 18, 2015 }}</ref>\n|date        = {{start date|2011|07|05}}\n|time        = 8:30 PM [[Pacific Standard Time|PDT]] (03:30 UTC)\n|place       = [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], [[California]], United States\n|participants = [[Fullerton Police Department]] officers Manuel Ramos, Jay Cicinelli, and Joseph Wolfe\n|charges = [[Second-degree murder]] (Class A Felony) (Manuel Ramos)<br>[[Involuntary manslaughter]] (Class A Felony) (Ramos, Jay Cicinelli, Joseph Wolfe)<br>Excessive force (Cicinelli, Wolfe)\n|verdict = Not guilty of all charges (Ramos, Cicinelli)<br>No verdict for Wolfe (charges were dropped)\n}}\n'''Kelly Thomas''' (April 5, 1974 \u2013 July 10, 2011) was a homeless man diagnosed with [[schizophrenia]] who lived on the streets of [[Fullerton, California]]. He was beaten to death by six members of the [[Fullerton Police Department]], on July 5, 2011.<ref name=\"Wolfedrop\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/kelly-thomas-fullerton-police-officers-beating-trial-joseph-wolfe-charges-dropped/1972899/|title=Third Ex-Fullerton Police Officer Won\u2019t Face Charges in Kelly Thomas Death}}</ref> Thomas was taken to [[St. Jude Medical Center]] before being transferred to the [[UC Irvine Medical Center]], where he was comatose on arrival and not expected to recover. He never regained consciousness, and died on July 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fatal Fullerton police beating of homeless man sparks outcry |first=Abby |last=Sewell |first2=Kate |last2=Mather |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/08/fatal-fullerton-police-beating-of-homeless-man-sparks-outcry.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 2, 2011}}</ref><ref name=timeline>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Timeline-The-Kelly-Thomas-Case-in-Fullerton-126851443.html |title=Timeline: The Kelly Thomas Case |last1=Lloyd |first1=Jonathan |date=Jan 13, 2014 |publisher=[[NBC Southern California]] |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nMedical records show that bones in his face were broken and he choked on his own blood.<ref>{{cite web|author=Amy Taxin & Greg Risling |url=https://news.yahoo.com/apnewsbreak-ca-police-officer-charged-murder-175213929.html |title=APNewsBreak: CA police officer charged with murder |publisher=Yahoo News |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> The coroner concluded that compression of the [[thorax]] made it impossible for Thomas to breathe normally and deprived his brain of oxygen.<ref name=Christine21 /> His parents removed him from life support five days later, and he died from his injuries on July 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Denisse Salazar |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/officers-307824-thomas-goodrich.html |title=Man who scuffled with police dies |publisher=OC Register |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Officer Manuel Ramos was charged with one count of [[Murder (United States law)#Degrees of murder in the United States|second-degree murder]] and one count of [[involuntary manslaughter]]; Corporal Jay Cicinelli and Officer Joseph Wolfe were each charged with one count of felony involuntary manslaughter and one count of [[excessive force]].<ref name=Christine21>{{cite news |title=2 police officers charged in death of Calif man |first=Christina |last=Ng |last2=Risling |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/kelly-thomas-police-officers-charged-beating-death-homeless/story?id=14575028 |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Ian Lovett |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/us/california-police-charged-in-killing.html?scp=4&sq=%22kelly%20thomas%22&st=cse |title=California: Police Charged in Killing |work=[[New York Times]] |date=September 22, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Grand jury: Third Fullerton officer beat Kelly Thomas |author=Nicole Santa Cruz |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/10/grand-jury-testimony-says-third-officer-used-excessive-force-.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=October 11, 2012 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> All three pleaded not guilty.\n\nA judge declined to dismiss the charges against the officers in January 2013, finding that \"a reasonable person could infer that the use of force was excessive and unreasonable.\"<ref name=\"dismiss1\">{{cite news |title=Judge Turns Down Dismissal Request in Kelly Thomas Case |author=Tracy Wood |url=http://www.voiceofoc.org/countywide/this_just_in/article_9649b5c8-5c70-11e2-9dfa-001a4bcf887a.html |newspaper=Voice of OC |date=January 11, 2012 |accessdate=January 11, 2012}}</ref> An appeals court judge also denied a request to overturn the lower court's decision.<ref name=\"dismiss2\">{{cite news|title=Court won't toss charges against ex-cop in Kelly Thomas death |author=Abby Sewell |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2013/03/kelly-thomas-officer-appeal-denied.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref> On January 13, 2014, Ramos and Cicinelli were found not guilty of all charges,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lopez |first=Andrew |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Former-Fullerton-Officers-Manuel-Ramos-Found-by-Jury-in-Kelly-Thomas-Trial-239924741.html?_osource=SocialFlowFB_LABrand |title=Jury Finds Ex-Officers Accused in Kelly Thomas Death Not Guilty &#124; NBC Southern California |publisher=Nbclosangeles.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> while the trial for Wolfe was pending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ktla.com/2014/01/13/verdict-reached-in-trial-of-ex-officers-in-kelly-thomas-death |title=Ex-Officers Found Not Guilty in Kelly Thomas\u2019 Beating Death &#124; KTLA 5 |publisher=Ktla.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> Following the verdict for the two officers, the district attorney's office announced it would not pursue the case against Wolfe.<ref>{{cite news\n | last1 = Flores   | first1 = Adolfo\n | last2 = Esquivel | first2 = Paloma\n | url = https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-live-verdict-in-kelly-thomas-police-murder-case-20140113,0,5661959.story\n | title = Police not guilty in Kelly Thomas death; DA won't try 3rd officer\n | work = Los Angeles Times\n | date = January 13, 2014\n | access-date = September 14, 2014\n}}</ref> On January 17, 2014, charges against Wolfe were dropped.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Kelly Thomas 2009 booking photo released by Fullerton PD.jpg|thumb|Kelly Thomas as he appeared in a 2009 booking photo released by Fullerton PD]]\nKelly Thomas was born April 5, 1974, to Ron Thomas, a former [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] Sheriff's deputy,<ref>{{cite web |last=Lopez |first=Steve |title=Kelly Thomas' father fights for justice |date=August 6, 2011 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/06/local/la-me-0807-lopez-kellythomas-20110805 |accessdate=September 22, 2011}}</ref> and Cathy Thomas.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-fullerton-death-pictures,0,3009403.photogallery?index=la-me004_homeless.5.gmf|title= Homeless man dies after run-in with Fullerton police|first= Gina |last=Ferazzi|date= August 2, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Thomas, who was diagnosed with schizophrenia, was a \"fixture\" among Fullerton's homeless population.<ref>{{cite news |title=Embattled Fullerton police chief goes on medical leave |first=Abby |last=Sewell |first2=Richard |last2=Winton |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-fullerton-death-20110811,0,6106396.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> The death of Thomas has sparked debate about systemic reforms in treatment of the mentally ill.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/08/local/la-me-kelly-thomas-mental-20120509 |title=Kelly Thomas video a turning point for mental health care? |author=Scott Gold, Richard Winton and Abby Sewell |date=May 8, 2012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1990 and 2011, Thomas had 92 encounters with the police. These encounters ranged from minor infractions such as trespassing to a guilty plea in an assault with a deadly weapon case sixteen years prior.<ref name=ocr20121018>{{cite news|title=Kelly Thomas: 92 police encounters since 1990|url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-374958-police-attorney.html|accessdate=October 18, 2012|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=October 18, 2012|author=Irving, Doug|author2=Ponsi, Lou}}</ref><ref name=abc />\n\n==Incident==\n[[File:Kelly-Thomas-pool-of-blood-crime-scene-exhibit-photo.jpg|thumb|right|The crime scene in the immediate aftermath of the beating]]\n\n[[File:Kelly-Thomas-Police-Beating.jpg|thumb|Kelly Thomas, after the attack from the officers of the Fullerton, California Police Department]]\nOn July 5, 2011, at about 8:30 PM, officers of the Fullerton Police Department responded to a call from the management of the Slidebar<ref name=\"slidebar\" /> that someone was vandalizing cars near the [[Fullerton (train station)|Fullerton Transportation Center]]. While investigating, they encountered the shirtless and disheveled Thomas and attempted to search him. According to statements given by the officers, Thomas was uncooperative and resisted when they attempted to search him, so backup was called.<ref name=\"LATimesEarly\">{{cite web|author=Kate Mather and Abby Sewell |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0803-fullerton-death-20110803,0,4180513.story |title=Fullerton police beating of homeless man is under investigation |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 2, 2011 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> \"Now you see my fists?\" Fullerton police officer Manuel Ramos asked Thomas while slipping on a pair of latex gloves. \"Yeah, what about them?\" Thomas responded. \"They are getting ready to fuck you up,\" said Ramos, to which Thomas replied, \"Start punching, dude\". A video of the event surfaced. Thomas can be seen being uncooperative with the officers, but sitting and being non-aggressive. After the officers grab Thomas to arrest him for stolen mail they apparently found, Thomas can be heard repeatedly screaming in pain while officers are heard repeatedly asking him to place his arms behind his back. He audibly responds \"Okay, I'm sorry!\" and \"I'm trying!\" while the officers stretch his arm back. The police officers claim that, unable to get Thomas to comply with the requests, they used a [[taser]] on him (up to five times according to a witness statement, and the video footage), and in the video Thomas can be heard screaming for his father.<ref name=\"LATimesEarly\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=friendsforfullerton |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ljYNgLnpxM |title=Police Beating of Kelly Thomas in Fullerton, CA |publisher=YouTube |date=July 23, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Six officers were involved in subduing Thomas, who was unarmed and had a history of mental illness. Thomas was initially taken to St. Jude Medical Center in Fullerton but was transferred immediately to the [[UC Irvine Medical Center]] with severe injuries to his head, face, and neck.<ref>{{cite web|author=Eliza Fisher |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/27/police-beat-homeless-full_n_911419.html |title=Police Beat Homeless Fullerton Man Kelly Thomas To Death |publisher=Huffington Post |date=July 27, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> One of the paramedics testified that he was first instructed to attend to a police officer's minor injury and then noticed Thomas lying unconscious in a pool of blood.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?id=9349329| author=Eileen Frere| title=Kelly Thomas trial: Forensic expert, paramedic testify| publisher=ABC News| date=December 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/officers-acquitted-in-death-of-kelly-thomas/2014/01/14/3e660b24-7d24-11e3-95c6-0a7aa80874bc_story.html |title=Officers acquitted in death of Kelly Thomas |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref>\n\nOrange County District Attorney [[Tony Rackauckas]] gave a detailed account of the events during a press conference on September 21, 2011. Using digital audio recording devices carried by the officers, surveillance video from a pole camera<ref>{{YouTube|KU0Imk2Bstg|surveillance video from a pole camera}}</ref> at the Fullerton Transportation Center, and other evidence, Rackauckas provided evidence that Thomas did comply with orders from Ramos, who had put on latex gloves and asked Thomas \"Now see my fists? They are getting ready to fuck you up.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Welsh |url=http://documents.latimes.com/charges-kelly-thomas-police/ |title=Charges against police in homeless man\u2019s death |work=LA Times |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Rackauckas went on to describe how Thomas begged for his life, before being struck repeatedly by the officers. He was admitted to the hospital, slipped into a coma, and died five days later.<ref>{{cite web|author=Abby Sewell and Richard Winton |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/09/kelly-thomas-begged-for-his-life-from-menacing-officer-da-says.html |title=Kelly Thomas begged for his life from 'menacing' officer, D.A. says |work=LA Times |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe story of his beating broke shortly before his death.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sean Emery |url=http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-07-06/news/29748743_1_goodrich-life-threatening-injuries-officers |title=Man who scuffled with police still in critical condition |publisher=OC Register |date=July 6, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715202530/http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-07-06/news/29748743_1_goodrich-life-threatening-injuries-officers |archivedate=July 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sam Quinones |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/07/homeless-man-dies-5-days-after-fight-with-fullerton-police-.html |title=Homeless man dies 5 days after fight with Fullerton police |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> An investigation into the beating was undertaken by the Orange County district attorney starting on July 7, 2011,<ref name=Ponsi4>{{cite news |title=ACLU: D.A. should not investigate fatal police fight |first=Lou |last=Ponsi |url=http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-08-04/news/29856409_1_police-officers-investigation-aclu |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130202213/http://articles.ocregister.com/2011-08-04/news/29856409_1_police-officers-investigation-aclu |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |newspaper=The Orange County Register |date=August 4, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 }}</ref> and later the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] became involved.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/orange_county&id=8279826 |title=FBI investigating Fullerton police beating |publisher=KABC-TV Los Angeles |date=July 30, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> The decision to involve the FBI was praised by the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], which claims the Orange County district attorney has an \"abysmal\" record when investigating shootings with police involvement.<ref name=Ponsi4 />\n\nKelly Thomas was removed from life support and died on July 10, 2011, five days after the beating.<ref name=abc>{{cite web|author= |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/orange_county&id=8243047 |title=Family says beaten man at hands of Fullerton police taken off life support |publisher=KABC-TV Los Angeles |date=July 10, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Initial reports claimed that Thomas had been very combative with officers and two had suffered broken bones.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/orange_county&id=8244594 |title=Family seeks witnesses to Fullerton police beating |publisher=KABC-TV Los Angeles |date=July 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> Later, the police department confirmed that no officers had suffered any broken bones, and that no one other than Thomas had any significant injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alex Stouffer |url=http://fullertonian.com/Blogs/tabid/97/ArticleType/ArticleView/ArticleID/408/Default.aspx |title=Protests & The Investigation of Kelly Thomas\u2019s Death |publisher=Fullertonian |date=July 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> By the end of July, several news outlets had picked up the story and it had become international news.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Quigley |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2019225/Kelly-Thomas-Police-beat-taser-gentle-mentally-ill-homeless-man-death.html |title=Caught on tape: Police beat and taser 'gentle' mentally-ill homeless man to death |work=Daily Mail |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2011, a large protest outside the Fullerton Police Department was organized by several people, including the victim's father Ron Thomas.<ref>{{cite web|author=E.D. Kain |url=https://blogs.forbes.com/erikkain/2011/07/30/protests-investigation-follow-police-beating-of-kelly-thomas/ |title=Protests, Investigation Follow Police Beating of Kelly Thomas |publisher=Forbes.com |date=July 30, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Fullerton City Council.jpg|thumb|Ron Thomas speaks to the Fullerton City Council and the media]]\nOn August 2, 2011 many members of the public spoke out about the beating at the biweekly city council meeting at the Fullerton City Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fullerton.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=2&clip_id=295 |archive-date=December 8, 2011|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20111208121027/http://fullerton.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id%3D2%26clip_id%3D295 |url-status=dead|title=City Council/Redevelopment Agency Regular Meeting |publisher=City of Fullerton, California |date=August 2, 2011 |accessdate=August 7, 2011 }}</ref> Over 70 members of the public spoke to the city council, the vast majority of whom criticized the police. Among the speakers was Ron Thomas, the father of Kelly Thomas, as well as Kelly Thomas's stepmother. The public comment session lasted for approximately three hours. The city attorney emphasized that the city council could not respond to the comments, however following the public comment period discussion was given to provide clarification on the city's policy regarding the mentally ill. In addition, Tony Bushala, a local developer and conservative activist, announced plans to recall three members of the city council thought to have responded insufficiently to the beating.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ian Lovett |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/04/us/04homeless.html |title=Death of Homeless Man After Beating by Police Stirs Outrage |work=The New York Times |date=August 3, 2011 |accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> The recall qualified on the ballot in February 2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/02/fullerton-recall.html |title=Recall election OKd for three Fullerton City Council members |author=Abby Sewell |date= February 6, 2012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> with a recall election scheduled for Don Bankhead, F. Dick Jones, and Pat McKinley on June 5, 2012, consolidated with the statewide primary election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityoffullerton.com/depts/city_clerk/elections/june_election/default.asp |title=Special Recall Election |author=City of Fullerton |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> On June 5, 2012 all three council members were successfully recalled by Fullerton residents.<ref>{{cite web|author=Abby Sewell |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/07/local/la-me-0607-fullerton-20120607-1 |title=Successful Fullerton City Council recall paves way for change |work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 7, 2012 |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday August 6, 2011, a large street protest was held outside of the Fullerton City Hall. Activists at that protest, which was attended by hundreds of people, called for the release of a surveillance video shot by cameras installed at the bus depot and carried signs with slogans like \"Jail All Killer Cops\" and \"End Police Brutality.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Winton and Abby Sewell |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-fullerton-death-20110807,0,6368545.story |title=Hundreds protest Fullerton man's death, call for release of video |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=August 6, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn late September 2011, the officers involved were arrested on murder charges. Local law enforcement personnel showed support by raising money for their bail and criminal defense.<ref>\"Friends of Fullerton's Future website, retrieved May 9, 2012</ref>\n\nThirty days after the incident all six officers involved in the beating were placed on [[administrative leave]] with pay and benefits intact. Several people, including two members of the Fullerton City Council, called for the resignation of police Chief Michael Sellers,<ref>{{cite web|author=Abby Sewell and Richard Winton |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0804-fullerton-death-20110804,0,5949987.story |title=Fullerton police draw fire for silence in homeless man's death |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 4, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> who was later placed on medical leave in August 2011 for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/11/local/la-me-fullerton-death-20110811 |title=Embattled Fullerton police chief goes on medical leave |author=Abby Sewell and Richard Winton |date=August 11, 2011 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Sellers continued his medical leave for 7 months and resigned on February 18, 2012 having never returned to work.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/sellers-338806-chief-city.html |title=Beleaguered Fullerton police chief to retire |publisher=Orange County Register |date=Aug 21, 2013 |author=Michael Mello |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> 19,948 people have signed an online petition calling for the firing of all six police officers that were present during the beating.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |title=Over 14K People Want Fullerton Police Officers Fired for Murder of Kelly Thomas |author=Lauren Lloyd |date=October 24, 2011 |publisher=LAist |accessdate=October 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018231753/http://laist.com/2011/10/24/fullerton_police_campaign.php |archivedate=October 18, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFullerton City Councilman Bruce Whitaker later went on television stating his belief that there was a cover-up of the beating of Thomas within the police department and that the six officers involved in the beating falsified their reports on the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://voiceofoc.org/oc_north/article_6ca7dad0-fac2-11e0-a80e-001cc4c002e0.html |title=Councilman Alleges Cover-Up in Kelly Thomas Police Beating |author=Nick Gerda |date=October 25, 2011 |work= |publisher=Voice of OC |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA preliminary hearing to determine if there is sufficient evidence for a trial was held on May 9, 2012. The court ordered that two of the police officers involved will stand trial. Manuel Ramos was charged with second-degree murder and involuntary manslaughter, and Jay Cicinelli was charged with involuntary manslaughter and felony use of excessive force. Both officers pleaded not guilty at the second arraignment on July 13, 2012.<ref name=ocr20120714>{{cite news|last=Welborn|first=Larry|title=Officers plead not guilty in death of Kelly Thomas|newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=July 14, 2012|pages=Local 1, 3}}</ref> Attempts by the defendants to dismiss the charges were denied.<ref name=\"dismiss1\" /><ref name=\"dismiss2\" /> In September 2012, Officer Joseph Wolfe was indicted on charges of involuntary manslaughter and use of excessive force.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/27/joseph-wolfe-kelly-thomas_n_1921322.html |title=Joseph Wolfe Arrested In Kelly Thomas Beating Death: Third Fullerton Police Officer Charged |author=Amy Taxin |date=September 27, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2013 |publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2012, press reports indicated that the Fullerton City Council had agreed to pay Thomas' mother one million dollars as a settlement of her civil complaints against the city. This did not impact the ongoing civil actions by Thomas' father or the criminal trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/16/local/la-me-0516-kelly-thomas-settlement-20120516 |title=Homeless man's mother settles with Fullerton over his death |author=Richard Winton |date=16 May 2012|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nTrials for Cicinelli and Ramos were scheduled to begin October 18, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2013/07/05/38055/kelly-thomas-beating-two-years-later-ex-fullerton/|title=Kelly Thomas beating: 2 years later, ex-Fullerton police officers face trial|first=Ed|last=Joyce|date=July 5, 2013|publisher=Southern California Public Radio}}</ref> but actually began on December 2, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Welborn|first=Larry|title=D.A.: Officer fueled routine meeting into Thomas death|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/thomas-539675-ramos-officers.html|accessdate=December 2, 2013|newspaper=The Orange County Register|date=December 2, 2013|author2=Jolly, Vik}}</ref> Proceedings concluded on January 13, 2014 with both Ramos and Cicinelli being found not guilty of any criminal charges.<ref name=verdict>{{cite web|last=Pamer|first=Melissa|title=Ex-Officers Found Not Guilty in Kelly Thomas\u2019 Beating Death |url=http://ktla.com/2014/01/13/verdict-reached-in-trial-of-ex-officers-in-kelly-thomas-death/#axzz2qKOGQwjZ|accessdate=14 January 2014|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> After the verdicts, the District Attorney's office announced that it would not proceed with Wolfe's trial.\n\nThe protests picked up again after the acquittals. On January 18, 2014, 14 people were arrested for protesting after ignoring a dispersal order from the police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-kelly-thomas-protest-update-20140118-story.html|title=At least 10 protesters arrested at Fullerton rally for Kelly Thomas|date=January 19, 2014|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 2017, federal prosecutors announced that they would not bring charges against former officers Ramos, Cicinelli and Wolfe for violating Thomas' civil rights.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ocregister.com/2017/01/24/kelly-thomas-case-5-years-later-feds-say-no-criminal-charges-against-fullerton-police-officers/| author=Sean Emery| title=Kelly Thomas case: 5 years later, feds say no criminal charges against Fullerton police officers| publisher=The Orange County Register| date=January 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Slidebar Kitchen involvement===\nIn June 2012 Michael Reeves, a former employee of the Slidebar Rock-N-Roll Kitchen, filed a lawsuit for wrongful termination against Jeremy Popoff related to the beating.<ref name=\"reeve2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/thomas-358499-police-reeves.html |title=Suit: False report sent police to Kelly Thomas |first1=Doug|last1=Irving|first2=Lou|last2= Ponsi |date=Jun 13, 2012 |work=OC Register |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/kelly-thomas-ron-thomas-jeremy-popoff-slidebar-fullerton-michael-reeves-jeanette-demarco-lawsuit-homeless-158691165.html |title=$16M Lawsuit Claims Restaurant Falsely Reported Kelly Thomas to Police |author=Caroline Tan and Vikki Vargas |date=Jun 13, 2012 |work= |publisher=NBC-LA |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> The Slidebar, which is owned by Popoff, the guitarist for [[Lit (band)|Lit]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2012/06/12/fullerton-bar-owner-denies-false-report-led-to-homeless-mans-death/|title=Fullerton Bar Owner Denies False Report Led To Homeless Man's Death|date=June 12, 2012}}</ref> was the source of the call that caused police to report to the area and confront Thomas.<ref name=\"slidebar\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2011/08/slidebar_kelly_thomas_call_police.php |title=&#91;UPDATE: Thomas' Previous Slidebar Encounters&#93; Sources: Slidebar Kitchen Placed Call Resulting in Kelly Thomas' Death |author=Brandon Ferguson |date=Aug 23, 2011 |work= |publisher=OC Weekly |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Reeves, a bouncer at the establishment, made statements to investigators claiming the Slidebar had a policy to do \"anything necessary\" to keep loiterers out of the area and that his manager lied about Thomas breaking into cars when calling the police to get them to respond more quickly.<ref name=\"reeve\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/13/kelly-thomas-beating-death-lawsuit-false-police-report-slidebar_n_1594253.html |title=Kelly Thomas Beating: Lawsuit Alleges Slidebar's 'False' Police Report Led To Thomas' Death |author=Anna Almendrala |date=June 6, 2012 |work= |publisher=Huffington Post |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> He further claims that Thomas was only loitering in the area that night and not causing trouble. Soon after making statements to investigators about what he saw that night he claims his managers were \"furious at him for it\" and slowly started taking away his responsibilities, culminating with his firing two months later.<ref name=\"reeve\" /> Reeves also claims that Popoff wanted everyone working at the Slidebar to act as if the \"Slidebar had nothing to do\" with the beating of Thomas and his refusal to echo these statements is the chief reason why he was fired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2012/06/slidebar_jeremy_popoff_lawsuit.php |title=Lawsuit: Fullerton Bar Manager Enticed Police with a Lie Before Officers Beat Kelly Thomas to Death |author=R. Scott Moxley |date= June 12, 2012 |work= |publisher=OC Weekly |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Eric Dubin, an attorney representing the Slidebar and Popoff, claims the suit is without merit and that it should be quickly dismissed. Dubin claims that \"This whole thing is all copy from blogs and sold to some lawyer\" and that, while the call did originate from the Slidebar, \"that she [the manager] never used the phrase 'breaking into cars.'\" Dubin further claims that \"Everything in that lawsuit is 100 percent false\"<ref name=\"reeve\" /> and the real reason Reeve was fired was because of a confrontation with a manager in front of customers.<ref name=\"reeve2\" /> On June 12, 2012, Ron Thomas organized a small gathering outside of the Slidebar to protest the false police report.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fullertonstories.com/lawsuit-highlights-call-to-police-in-kelly-thomas-case/ |title=Lawsuit Highlights Call To Police in Kelly Thomas Case |author= |date=June 12, 2012 |work= |publisher=Fullerton Stories |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Thomas and Popoff talked during the event and Thomas later said that if the report was correct, \"then I have no beef\" but that if there are any inconsistencies then \"I have to do what I have to do\".\n\nOne day after this statement, on June 13, 2012, after months of denials, Slidebar owner Jeremy Popoff stated on [[KFI]]'s [[John and Ken|John and Ken Show]] that one of his employees did, in fact, call police the night Kelly Thomas was beaten. He declined to say what the employee reported, citing the criminal investigation into Thomas' death, but said a recording of the call has been reviewed by the District Attorney's Office and other investigators.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-358721-officers-slidebar.html |title=Bouncer: I knew Kelly Thomas report was false |author=Doug Irving |date=June 13, 2012 |work= |publisher=Orange County Register |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Popoff and his lawyer denied the claims of an anti-homeless policy during a press conference.\n\nThe issue was eventually solved in a settlement.<ref>Ponsi, Lou. [http://www.ocregister.com/articles/reeves-519774-slidebar-thomas.html \"Ex-bouncer's Lawsuit in Kelly Thomas Death Settled.\"] The Orange County Register. The OC Register, 5 August 2013. Retrieved 15 December 2014.</ref> This sparked renewed protests in front of the Slidebar Kitchen.\n\n===Cause of death===\nOn September 21, 2011, Orange County district attorney [[Tony Rackauckas]] held a press conference to announce the results of the investigation. Rackauckas announced that according to the Orange County coroner, the cause of death was \"[[asphyxia]] caused by mechanical chest compression with blunt cranial-facial injuries sustained during physical altercation with law enforcement.\" Rackauckas said Thomas died because of the force of the officers on his chest, which made it impossible for him to breathe, causing Thomas to become unconscious. He then became comatose, and died when taken off life support five days later.\n\nAccording to Rackauckas, the coroner stated that the injuries to Thomas' face and head contributed to his death. Also contributing to his death were brain injuries, facial and rib fractures, and the extensive bruising and abrasions he suffered during the beating, which left him lying in a \"growing pool of blood\", Rackauckas said. The toxicology report shows that Thomas had no illicit drugs or alcohol in his system.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alyssa Newcomb |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/kelly-thomas-beating-video-fullerton-officers-court/story?id=16302273#.T-9VYEMy7dX |title=California Judge to Decide Whether Cops Will Stand Trial for Beating Homeless Man |publisher=ABC |date=May 8, 2012 |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Thomas was severely bleeding and struggled and pleaded, \"I can't breathe,\" \"Dad, help me.\" The DA stated that the officers did not reduce their level of force during the nearly 10-minute assault.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-318320-death-rackauckas.html?nstrack=sid:2589472%7Cmet:102%7Ccat:227%7Corder:1 |title=Kelly Thomas died of asphyxia, report says |author=Denisse Salazar |date=September 21, 2011 |work= |publisher=Voice of OC |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, Dr. Gary Vilke (a professor of clinical emergency medicine at UC San Diego) testified for the defense during the trial. He has investigated in-custody deaths for 20 years and has published studies on \"mechanical compression.\"<ref name=\"KPCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/01/09/41476/kelly-thomas-trial-da-makes-final-appeal-jurors-be/ |title=Kelly Thomas Trial: DA makes final appeal, jurors begin deliberations (updated) &#124; 89.3 KPCC |publisher=Scpr.org |date=2014-01-09 |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref> He testified, \u201cI know he was breathing when the officers got off him because he was still talking.\"  \"As far as the cause of death, it\u2019s not asphyxiation.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|last=Flores |first=Adolfo |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-kelly-thomas-did-not-die-of-asphyxiation-witness-says-20131216,0,3491049.story#ixzz2qhqqOuZu |title=Kelly Thomas did not die of asphyxiation, expert witness testifies |publisher=latimes.com |date=2013-12-16 |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref> The defense also implied medical treatment could have played a part in Thomas's death (hospital records reportedly showed that a tube placed down his windpipe to assist his breathing had been pushed too far).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kabc.com/common/page.php?pt=Prosecution+Takes+a+Beating+in+the+Kelly+Thomas+Trial&id=22553&is_corp=0 |title=Prosecution Takes a Beating in the Kelly Thomas Trial |publisher=[[KABC (AM)]] |accessdate=2014-01-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224857/http://www.kabc.com/common/page.php?pt=Prosecution+Takes+a+Beating+in+the+Kelly+Thomas+Trial&id=22553&is_corp=0 |archivedate=2014-02-01 }}</ref> The prosecution dismissed these claims, saying they did not apply and their value was not great enough.<ref name=\"KPCC\"/>\n\n===Lawsuit by father===\nWithin days after the incident, Ron Thomas, the father of Kelly Thomas, retained noted personal injury and civil rights attorney [[Garo Mardirossian]] to represent him in a civil action against the City of Fullerton and the involved officers. Mr. Mardirossian then held several press conferences to address bringing criminal charges against Officer Manuel Ramos, Corporal Jay Cicinelli, and Officer Joseph Wolfe, and the civil lawsuit filed against the City. These press conferences aired locally, nationally, and internationally heightening public interest, and imposing pressure on the Orange County District Attorney to file criminal charges.\n\nIn the civil proceedings, Cathy Thomas, the mother of Kelly Thomas, settled for $1 million. Cathy Thomas was represented by another lawyer.\n\nDespite the subsequent not guilty verdicts in favor of Officer Ramos and Corporal Cicinelli, Mr. Mardirossian obtained a $4.9 million settlement just before Manuel Ramos, the chief perpetrator, was to testify in the civil jury trial. The settlement precluded the officers who were fired from being re-hired by Fullerton Police Department.\n\n===Criminal trial===\nOn January 13, 2014, Manuel Ramos was acquitted of second-degree murder and involuntary manslaughter in the 2011 death of Thomas. Jay Cicinelli was acquitted of involuntary manslaughter and excessive use of force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2014/01/14/kelly-thomas-trial-officers-acquitted-in-homeless-man-death/ |title=Kelly Thomas trial: Officers acquitted in homeless man's death |author=Associated Press |date=January 14, 2014 |work= |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=January 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Recall election===\nIn a landslide June 5, 2012 recall election, city council members Dick Jones, Don Bankhead and Pat McKinley were voted out of office. Each was voted out by an almost identical majority of nearly 66%. Their replacements were: Travis Kiger, a planning commissioner and blogger for the site Friends for Fullerton's Future, who filled Jones' term, which expired December 4, 2012; Greg Sebourn, a land surveyor, who filled Bankhead's term, which also ended December 4; and attorney Doug Chaffee, who filled McKinley's term, which ended December 2, 2012. All were sworn into office in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/07/local/la-me-0607-fullerton-20120607-1 |title=Successful Fullerton City Council recall paves way for change |author= Abby Sewell |date=June 7, 2012 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> Tony Bushala, a leading organizer of the Fullerton recall election, said he was seeking accountability for Kelly Thomas' death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2012-06-06/us/us_california-fullerton-recall-election_1_involuntary-manslaughter-election-officials-homeless-man?_s=PM:US |title=3 California councilmen ousted in recall over alleged police brutality |author=Michael Martinez and Casey Wian |date=June 6, 2012 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=July 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619223600/http://articles.cnn.com/2012-06-06/us/us_california-fullerton-recall-election_1_involuntary-manslaughter-election-officials-homeless-man?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=June 19, 2012 }}</ref> The city's other two council members did not face a recall.\n\n===Employment termination===\nOn July 3, 2012, Ramos' employment was terminated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sewell|first=Abby |title=Officer charged in Kelly Thomas' death leaves police force |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/07/fullerton-officer-no-longer-employed.html |accessdate=July 11, 2012 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\nAccording to a statement issued by Fullerton Police, Joe Wolfe is no longer employed by the department as of July 16, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Kelly-Thomas-Manuel-Ramos-Jay-Cicinelli-Officer-Joe-Wolfe-Fullerton-Police-Department-162824596.html |title=Two Officers Involved in Kelly Thomas Beating No Longer Work for City: Police |first=Samantha|last= Tata |date=July 17, 2012 |publisher=NBC Southern California}}</ref>\nJay Cicinelli is no longer employed by Fullerton Police as of July 20, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/thomas-364830-officers-cicinelli.html |title=Kelly Thomas case: Third officer no longer employed |publisher=ocregister.com |date=July 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Anonymous response===\n\nIn August 2011, the Internet activist group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] demanded that the officers involved be prosecuted, the Fullerton Police Chief resign, and that Thomas's family be awarded US$5 million in compensation; they threatened to shut down the Fullerton municipal website if their demands were not met.<ref name=\"Almendrala2011\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/15/kelly-thomas-anonymous_n_927305.html|accessdate=2014-07-21|date=2011-10-15|first=Anna|last=Almendrala|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|title=Kelly Thomas Death Spurs 'Anonymous' Hackers To Action|publisher=[[AOL]]|archivedate=2014-02-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203011820/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/15/kelly-thomas-anonymous_n_927305.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2014, after the police officers involved were acquitted, Anonymous [[doxing|released their personal addresses]],<ref name=\"King2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/personal-info-of-cops-in-kelly-thomas-case-released-by-anonymous/article/366599|title=Personal info of cops in Kelly Thomas case released by Anonymous|last=King|first=Justin|date=2014-01-19|newspaper=Digital Journal|archivedate=2014-02-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203021315/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/personal-info-of-cops-in-kelly-thomas-case-released-by-anonymous/article/366599|url-status=live|accessdate=2014-07-21}}</ref> as well as the identities of the jurors.<ref name=\"Murphy2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/news/anonymous-opfullerton-kelly-thomas/|title=Anonymous's #OpFullerton seeks justice for Kelly Thomas|last=Murphy|first=Lorraine|date=2014-01-24|accessdate=2014-07-21|newspaper=[[The Daily Dot]]|archivedate=2014-04-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403151337/http://www.dailydot.com/news/anonymous-opfullerton-kelly-thomas/|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 18 and 19, Anonymous took down several websites belonging to or run by Fullerton police and municipality.<ref name=\"Murphy2014\"/><ref name=\"Amir2014\">{{cite news|url=http://hackread.com/anonymous-takes-down-fullerton-police-website-against-arrest/|title=#OpFullerton: Anonymous takes down Fullerton police website against protesters arrest and Kelly Thomas tribute|last=Amir|first=Waqas|date=2014-01-19|archivedate=2014-03-13|accessdate=2014-07-21|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313105824/http://hackread.com/anonymous-takes-down-fullerton-police-website-against-arrest/|work=HackRead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of killings by law enforcement officers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160419011555/http://fullertonfactcheck.com/kelly-thomas-a-quiet-gentle-soul/ ''Fullerton Stories'' has a brief write up about Thomas' life]\n*[http://www.fullertonsfuture.org/tag/kelly-thomas-beating/ ''Friends For Fullerton'', a blog with extensive coverage of the event]\n*{{YouTube|KU0Imk2Bstg|Security footage of the beating}}\n\n{{Fullerton, California}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Kelly}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Criminal trials that ended in acquittal]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths in police custody in the United States]]\n[[Category:Homeless people]]\n[[Category:People from Fullerton, California]]\n[[Category:History of Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:People with schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Victims of police brutality]]\n[[Category:2011 in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Filmed killings by law enforcement]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1014:d140:9c3:84fc:7fbb:b63a:44dc", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links:Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_of_Kelly_Thomas"}
{"title_page": "Kyriakos Mitsotakis", "text_new": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Greece}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kauliarhs Mitsotakis<br />{{small|{{lang|el|\u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}}}\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| image               = EPP Zagreb Congress in Croatia, 20-21 November 2019 (49099472986) (cropped) 2 (cropped).jpg\n| office              = [[Prime Minister of Greece]]\n| status              = \n| president           = [[Prokopis Pavlopoulos]]<br>[[Katerina Sakellaropoulou]]\n| deputy              = [[Panagiotis Pikrammenos]]\n| term_start          = 8 July 2019\n| term_end            = \n| succeeded           = \n| predecessor         = [[Alexis Tsipras]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[New Democracy (Greece)|President of New Democracy]]\n| vicepresident1      = [[Adonis Georgiadis]]<br>[[Kostis Hatzidakis]]\n| term_start1         = 10 January 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| primeminister2      = [[Alexis Tsipras]]\n| term_start2         = 10 January 2016\n| term_end2           = 8 July 2019\n| predecessor2        = [[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]\n| successor2          = [[Alexis Tsipras]]\n| office3             = [[Ministry of Digital Governance (Greece)|Minister of Administrative Reform]]\n| primeminister3      = [[Antonis Samaras]]\n| term_start3         = 25 June 2013\n| term_end3           = 27 January 2015\n| predecessor3        = [[Antonis Manitakis]]\n| successor3          = [[Nikos Voutsis]]\n| office4             = Member of the [[Hellenic Parliament]]<br />for Athens B2 (West)<br /><small>[[Athens B]] (2004-2019)</small>\n| term_start4         = 7 March 2004\n| term_end4           = \n| birth_name          = Kyriakos Mitsotakis\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1968|3|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]]\n| religion            = [[Greek Orthodox]]\n| father              = [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]]\n| spouse              = Mareva Grabowski\n| children            = 3\n| education           = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])<br />[[Stanford University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| signature           = Kyriakos Mitsotakis signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Kyriakos Mitsotakis''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 4 March 1968) is a Greek politician serving as [[Prime Minister of Greece]] since 8 July 2019. A member of [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]], he has been its president since 2016. Mitsotakis previously was [[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)|Leader of the Opposition]] from 2016 to 2019 and [[Ministry of Digital Governance (Greece)|Minister of Administrative Reform]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\nHe was first elected to the [[Hellenic Parliament]] for the [[Athens B]] [[List of parliamentary constituencies of Greece|constituency]] in [[2004 Greek legislative election|2004]]. After New Democracy suffered two election defeats in 2015, he was elected the party's leader in January 2016. Three years later, on 7 July 2019, he led his party to a majority in the [[2019 Greek legislative election|2019 election]], their first since [[2007 Greek legislative election|2007]]. He is the son of former Prime Minister [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]].<ref name=aljazeerajuly8inaug>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/07/pm-elect-vows-greece-proud-landslide-win-190708035649498.html|title=Kyriakos Mitsotakis sworn in as Greece's new prime minister|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=guardianjuly8inaug /><ref name=dwjuly8inaug />\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Athens]], he is the son of the former [[Prime Minister of Greece]] and honorary president of [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]], [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]], and his wife [[Marika Mitsotakis|Marika]] (n\u00e9e Giannoukou). At the time of his birth, his family had been placed under house arrest by the [[Greek military junta of 1967-1974|Greek military junta]] that had declared his father [[persona non grata]] and imprisoned him on the night of the coup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.gr/2016/07/22/politiki-mitsotakis-_n_11140290.html|title=\u0397 \u03b5\u03be\u03ae\u03b3\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \"\u03ad\u03be\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\": \u0397 \u03c7\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b4\u03b5\u03bd \u03ac\u03c6\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03b2\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c0\u03af\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|author=|date=22 July 2016|website=HuffPost Greece|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref> In 1968, when he was only 1 year old, the family escaped to [[Turkey]] with the help of then [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Turkish Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[\u0130hsan Sabri \u00c7a\u011flayangil]].  After a while, they moved from Turkey to [[Paris]] and waited until 1974 to return to Greece after [[Metapolitefsi|democracy had been restored]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Akten |first1=Serta\u00e7 |last2=Alan |first2=G\u00fcls\u00fcm |title=Yunanistan erken genel se\u00e7imleri ile ilgili bilmeniz gereken her \u015fey |url=https://tr.euronews.com/2019/07/03/yunanistan-erken-genel-secime-gidiyor-anketlere-gore-merkez-sag-onde |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=[[Euronews]] (T\u00fcrk\u00e7e) |date=July 4, 2019}}</ref> Later, Mitsotakis described the first six months of his life as [[Political prisoner|political imprisonment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dimokratiki.gr/22-07-2016/ti-apanta-o-kiriakos-mitsotakis-apo-facebook-oti-itan-politikos-kratoumenos-6-minon/|title=\u03a4\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac \u03bf \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf Facebook \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \"\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2, 6 \u03bc\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd\" - \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a1\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5|author=|date=22 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=1 February 2019|via=www.dimokratiki.gr}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, he graduated from [[Athens College]]. From 1986 to 1990, he attended [[Harvard University]] and earned a bachelor's degree in [[social studies]], receiving the [[Thomas T. Hoopes Prize|Hoopes]] and [[Prix Alexis de Tocqueville|Tocqueville]] prizes. From 1992 to 1993 he attended [[Stanford University]], earning a [[Ford Dorsey Master's in International Policy]]. From 1993 to 1995, he attended [[Harvard Business School]] where he earned an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]].<ref name=\"Concordia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.concordia.net/community/kyriakos-mitsotakis/|title=Kyriakos Mitsotakis|author=|date=|website=Concordia|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\nFrom 1990 to 1991 Kyriakos Mitsotakis worked as a [[financial analyst]] at the [[corporate finance]] division of [[Chase Bank]] in London. From 1991 to 1992, Mitsotakis returned to Greece and joined the [[Hellenic Army]] to fulfil his mandatory [[Conscription in Greece|national service]] obligations. From 1995 to 1997, and following the completion of his post-graduate studies, he was employed by the consultancy [[McKinsey & Company]] in London, focusing primarily on the [[telecommunication]]s and [[financial services]] industries. From 1997 to 1999 he worked for Alpha Ventures, a [[private equity]] subsidiary of [[Alpha Bank]], as a senior investment officer, executing venture capital and private equity transactions. In 1999 he founded NBG Venture Capital, the private equity and venture capital subsidiary of the [[National Bank of Greece]], and acted as its [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] until April 2003, when he resigned to pursue a career in politics, managing its portfolio and executing transactions in Greece and the [[Balkans]].<ref name=\"Concordia\" />\n\nIn January 2003 he was nominated by the [[World Economic Forum]] as a global leader of tomorrow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delphiforum.gr/speakers/kyriakos-mitsotakis|title=Kyriakos Mitsotakis - Delphi Economic Forum|author=|date=|website=www.delphiforum.gr|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDuring the [[2000 Greek legislative election|2000 legislative election]], Mitsotakis worked for New Democracy's national campaign. In the [[2004 Greek legislative election|2004 legislative election]], Mitsotakis ran in the [[Athens B (constituency)|Athens B]] constituency, receiving more votes than any other New Democracy candidate in the country and was elected to the [[Hellenic Parliament]].{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nMitsotakis is honorary president of Konstantinos K. Mitsotakis Foundation, aiming at promoting the life and works of [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]] and at reporting the modern political history of Greece.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn 24 June 2013, Mitsotakis was appointed as the [[Ministry of Administrative Reform and e-Governance (Greece)|Minister of Administrative Reform and e-Governance]] in [[Antonis Samaras]]' cabinet, succeeding [[Antonis Manitakis]]. He served in this position until January 2015. During this time, he pursued comprehensive national reforms by implementing a functional reorganization of institutions, structures and processes. He steadfastly supported the drastic downsizing of the [[Public Sector]] and the structural reform of the tax administration.\n\nIn 2015, Mitsotakis served as a parliamentary representative for New Democracy, representing the President of the party in Parliament, as well as the body of the party's Representatives. He was charged with expressing the positions of his party during Parliamentary procedures and discourse, as well as ensuring the proper function of Parliament through a process of checks and balances. In March 2015, he claimed that then-Minister of Finance [[Yanis Varoufakis]] was undermining the Greek negotiations over the [[Third Economic Adjustment Programme for Greece|third bailout programme]], saying: \"Every time he opens his mouth, he creates a problem for the country\u2019s negotiating position.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.ekathimerini.com/168038/article/ekathimerini/news/varoufakis-undermining-greek-negotiations-says-mitsotakis|title = Varoufakis undermining Greek negotiations, says Mitsotakis|last = |first = |date = 9 March 2015|work = Kathimerini|access-date = 20 January 2016|via = }}</ref>\n\n[[File:EPP Summit, Brussels, March 2016 (25834276136).jpg|thumb|left|Mitsotakis and Armenian President [[Serzh Sargsyan]] in 2016]]\nMitsotakis was the first of four New Democracy members to announce their candidacy in the [[New Democracy leadership election, 2015\u201316|leadership election]], declared following the resignation of [[Antonis Samaras]] as party leader and the failure of New Democracy in the [[September 2015 Greek legislative election|September 2015 snap election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.ekathimerini.com/201813/article/ekathimerini/news/mitsotakis-first-to-declare-will-run-for-nd-leadership|title = Mitsotakis first to declare will run for ND leadership|last = |first = |date = 22 September 2015|work = Kathimerini|access-date = 20 January 2016|via = }}</ref> Amongst the other contestants was then-interim leader and former [[Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament]] [[Vangelis Meimarakis]]. According to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', Mitsotakis was \"billed as an outsider in the leadership race\" due to the party establishment's support of Meimarakis' candidacy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/3509ba68-b7dc-11e5-bf7e-8a339b6f2164.html|title = Free-market reformer Mitsotakis wins vote to lead Greece opposition party|last = Hope|first = Kerin|date = 10 January 2016|work = Financial Times|access-date = 19 January 2016|via = }}</ref> Following the first round of voting with no clear winner, Mitsotakis came second, 11% behind Meimarakis.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:EPP Summit, Brussels, March 2017 (33212125861).jpg|thumb|Mitsotakis and Spanish Prime Minister [[Mariano Rajoy]] in 2017]]\nOn 10 January 2016, Mitsotakis was elected president of the [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]] political party succeeding [[Ioannis Plakiotakis]] (transitional president) with almost 4% difference from opponent [[Vangelis Meimarakis]]. A week following Mitsotakis' election as leader, two opinion polls were published that put New Democracy ahead of [[Syriza]] for the first time in a year.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://news.yahoo.com/greek-opposition-ahead-syriza-first-time-151535112.html|title = Greek opposition ahead of Syriza for first time in a year|last = |first = |date = 17 January 2016|agency= AFP|access-date = 19 January 2016|via = Yahoo News}}</ref>\n\nHis party won 33% of the votes in the European elections in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsit.gr/politikh/apotelesmata-eyroeklogon-2019-idou-i-teliki-katataksi-935-monades-i-diafora-6/2791810/|title=2019 european elections results|last=|first=|date=6 June 2019|website=NewsIt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He managed to win back votes from the [[Golden Dawn (political party)|Golden Dawn]] Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/grece-syriza-devancee-par-la-droite-conservatrice-672771|title=Gr\u00e8ce. Syriza devanc\u00e9e par la droite conservatrice|date=May 27, 2019|website=L'Humanit\u00e9|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref> Following the election results, the Hellenic Parliament was dissolved and a snap election was called.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/05/27/greece-headed-to-snap-elections-after-syriza-defeat-in-eu-vote|title=Greece headed to snap elections after Syriza defeat in EU vote|website=www.euronews.com|date=27 May 2019|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Greece==\n\nNew Democracy won a landslide victory in the [[2019 Greek legislative election|2019 legislative election]], scoring 39.85% of votes and securing 158 seats in the [[Hellenic Parliament]]. On 8 July 2019, Greek President [[Prokopis Pavlopoulos]] accepted Tsipras's resignation and tasked Mitsotakis with forming a new government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/07/08/greek-conservative-mitsotakis-sworn-in-as-prime-minister/|title=Greek conservative Mitsotakis sworn in as prime minister|last=Service|first=Reuters News|date=2019-07-08|website=Cyprus Mail|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> Mitsotakis was sworn in as Prime Minister the same day as well.<ref name=guardianjuly8inaug>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/08/kyriakos-mitsotakis-takes-over-greece-pm-new-democracy|title=Mitsotakis takes over as Greece's PM with radical change of style|first=Helena|last=Smith|date=Jul 8, 2019|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=dwjuly8inaug>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/greek-conservative-mitsotakis-sworn-in-as-prime-minister/a-49511142|title=Greek conservative Mitsotakis sworn in as prime minister &#124; DW &#124; 08.07.2019|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=aljazeerajuly8inaug /> On 9 July, the [[Cabinet of Kyriakos Mitsotakis|ministers in his government]] were sworn in.\n[[File:EPP Zagreb Congress in Croatia, 20-21 November 2019 (49099971307).jpg|thumb|Mitsotakis on the EPP [[Zagreb]] Congress, 2019]]\n\n== Personal life ==\nMitsotakis is the younger brother of former [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Greece)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] and [[Mayor of Athens]] [[Dora Bakoyannis]], making him the brother-in-law of the late [[Pavlos Bakoyannis]], who was assassinated by the terrorist group [[Revolutionary Organization 17 November|17 November]] in 1989 and the uncle of [[Kostas Bakoyannis]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/elections/news/greeces-top-family-dynasty-in-bid-for-pm-athens-mayor/|title=Greece's top family dynasty in bid for PM, Athens mayor|date=May 31, 2019|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref> former Regional Governor of [[Central Greece (region)|Central Greece]] and current [[Mayor of Athens]].\n\nMitsotakis is married to [[Mareva Grabowski]], an investment banker with Greek, Polish and Egyptian roots. They have three children, Sophia, Constantine and Daphne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greece.greekreporter.com/2019/07/09/mareva-grabowski-mitsotakis-meet-the-new-first-lady-of-greece/|author=Tasos Kokkinidis|title=Mareva Grabowski-Mitsotakis: Meet the New First Lady of Greece|date=Jul 7, 2019|website=GreekReporter.com|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Greek, he speaks English, French and German.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/140719/new-greek-pm-kyriakos-mitsotakis-is-a-scion-of-one-of-greeces-most-influential-political-families/|title=New Greek PM Kyriakos Mitsotakis is a scion of one of Greece's most influential political families &#124; Neos Kosmos|date=Jul 7, 2019|website=English Edition|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMitsotakis is a member of the [[Greek Orthodox Church]].\n\n==Controversy==\n=== Siemens scandal allegations ===\nIn 2007, it was reported that Mitsotakis was involved in the [[Siemens Greek bribery scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.enet.gr/online/online_text/c%3D110%2Cid%3D74151416%2C43446968%2C15515192%2C21432248%2C79944568%2C37645624%2C44118392 |title=\u0395\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03af\u03b1 - \u03a4\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \"\u0396\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03c2\" |accessdate=2017-05-09 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225084100/http://archive.enet.gr/online/online_text/c%3D110%2Cid%3D74151416%2C43446968%2C15515192%2C21432248%2C79944568%2C37645624%2C44118392 |archivedate=February 25, 2011 }}</ref> However, Mitsotakis has repeatedly denied any involvement and no indication of guilt has so far been proven. The Siemens trial, in which Mitsotakis is not involved, is still pending.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/1174442/ypothesi-siemens-stis-24-febrouariou-arxizei-i-diki|title=\u03a5\u03c0\u03cc\u03b8\u03b5\u03c3\u03b7 Siemens: \u03a3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 24 \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b7 &#124; naftemporiki.gr|date=November 22, 2016|website=www.naftemporiki.gr}}</ref>\n\nElectronic office equipment, call centers, air conditioners etc. worth approx. \u20ac130,000 were received in the period preceding the 2007 elections (June to September 2007) by Mitsotakis from Siemens and two of its subsidiaries. The invoices indicate payment period of up to 60 days, however no part of the amount was paid until February 2008, when part of it was paid, just when the Siemens case was reopened by the courts, and an amount of \u20ac43,850 was paid by check from Mr. Mitsotakis on Monday June 2. Earlier (on 29 May) testimonies had been made about \"donations and grants by Siemens to politicians\" and on 30 May 2008 the prosecutor's investigation took place at the company's offices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.protothema.gr/greece/article/9988/emplokh-kyr-mhtsotakh-sto-skandalo-siemens/|title=\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03ba\u03ac\u03bd\u03b4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf SIEMENS|date=2015-12-23|website=protothema.gr|language=greek|access-date=2008-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kathimerini.gr/324733/article/epikairothta/politikh/106-thlefwnikes-syskeyes-gia-ena-grafeio|title=107 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bb\u03b5\u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c5\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03ad\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1 \u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03af\u03bf|date=2015-12-23|website=kathimerini.gr|language=greek|access-date=2008-06-07}}</ref>\n\n== Venizelos/Mitsotakis family tree ==\n{{Venizelos/Mitsotakis family tree}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website}} {{in lang|en|el}}\n* {{Hellenic Parliament|d0750741-dbb8-4bec-9466-526fe9c11773|cv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antonis Manitakis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Administrative Reform and e-Governance|Minister of Administrative Reform]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nikos Voutsis]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2016\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alexis Tsipras]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alexis Tsipras]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Greece]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New Democracy (Greece)|President of New Democracy]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Katerina Sakellaropoulou]]|as=[[President of Greece|President of the Republic]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Greek order of precedence|Order of precedence of Greece]]<br />''{{small|as Prime Minister}}''|years=}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Konstantinos Tasoulas]]|as=[[Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament|Speaker of the Parliament]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Greece}}\n{{Current Cabinet of Greece}}\n{{Leaders of the Opposition of Greece}}\n{{Leaders of New Democracy}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{NATO leaders}}\n{{Vouli-database}}\n{{Portal bar|Greece|Politics|}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitsotakis, Kyriakos}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Greek bankers]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2004\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2007\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2009\u20132012]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2012 (May)]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2012\u20132014]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2015 (February\u2013August)]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2015\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Greece]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Leaders of New Democracy (Greece)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:McKinsey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Administrative Reform and e-Governance of Greece]]\n[[Category:Mitsotakis family|Kyriakos]]\n[[Category:New Democracy (Greece) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Athens]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Greece}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kyriakos Mitsotakis<br />{{small|{{lang|el|\u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}}}\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| image               = EPP Zagreb Congress in Croatia, 20-21 November 2019 (49099472986) (cropped) 2 (cropped).jpg\n| office              = [[Prime Minister of Greece]]\n| status              = \n| president           = [[Prokopis Pavlopoulos]]<br>[[Katerina Sakellaropoulou]]\n| deputy              = [[Panagiotis Pikrammenos]]\n| term_start          = 8 July 2019\n| term_end            = \n| succeeded           = \n| predecessor         = [[Alexis Tsipras]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[New Democracy (Greece)|President of New Democracy]]\n| vicepresident1      = [[Adonis Georgiadis]]<br>[[Kostis Hatzidakis]]\n| term_start1         = 10 January 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| primeminister2      = [[Alexis Tsipras]]\n| term_start2         = 10 January 2016\n| term_end2           = 8 July 2019\n| predecessor2        = [[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]\n| successor2          = [[Alexis Tsipras]]\n| office3             = [[Ministry of Digital Governance (Greece)|Minister of Administrative Reform]]\n| primeminister3      = [[Antonis Samaras]]\n| term_start3         = 25 June 2013\n| term_end3           = 27 January 2015\n| predecessor3        = [[Antonis Manitakis]]\n| successor3          = [[Nikos Voutsis]]\n| office4             = Member of the [[Hellenic Parliament]]<br />for Athens B2 (West)<br /><small>[[Athens B]] (2004-2019)</small>\n| term_start4         = 7 March 2004\n| term_end4           = \n| birth_name          = Kyriakos Mitsotakis\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1968|3|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]]\n| religion            = [[Greek Orthodox]]\n| father              = [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]]\n| spouse              = Mareva Grabowski\n| children            = 3\n| education           = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])<br />[[Stanford University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| signature           = Kyriakos Mitsotakis signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Kyriakos Mitsotakis''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 4 March 1968) is a Greek politician serving as [[Prime Minister of Greece]] since 8 July 2019. A member of [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]], he has been its president since 2016. Mitsotakis previously was [[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)|Leader of the Opposition]] from 2016 to 2019 and [[Ministry of Digital Governance (Greece)|Minister of Administrative Reform]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\nHe was first elected to the [[Hellenic Parliament]] for the [[Athens B]] [[List of parliamentary constituencies of Greece|constituency]] in [[2004 Greek legislative election|2004]]. After New Democracy suffered two election defeats in 2015, he was elected the party's leader in January 2016. Three years later, on 7 July 2019, he led his party to a majority in the [[2019 Greek legislative election|2019 election]], their first since [[2007 Greek legislative election|2007]]. He is the son of former Prime Minister [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]].<ref name=aljazeerajuly8inaug>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/07/pm-elect-vows-greece-proud-landslide-win-190708035649498.html|title=Kyriakos Mitsotakis sworn in as Greece's new prime minister|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=guardianjuly8inaug /><ref name=dwjuly8inaug />\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Athens]], he is the son of the former [[Prime Minister of Greece]] and honorary president of [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]], [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]], and his wife [[Marika Mitsotakis|Marika]] (n\u00e9e Giannoukou). At the time of his birth, his family had been placed under house arrest by the [[Greek military junta of 1967-1974|Greek military junta]] that had declared his father [[persona non grata]] and imprisoned him on the night of the coup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.gr/2016/07/22/politiki-mitsotakis-_n_11140290.html|title=\u0397 \u03b5\u03be\u03ae\u03b3\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \"\u03ad\u03be\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\": \u0397 \u03c7\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b4\u03b5\u03bd \u03ac\u03c6\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03b2\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c0\u03af\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|author=|date=22 July 2016|website=HuffPost Greece|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref> In 1968, when he was only 1 year old, the family escaped to [[Turkey]] with the help of then [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Turkish Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[\u0130hsan Sabri \u00c7a\u011flayangil]].  After a while, they moved from Turkey to [[Paris]] and waited until 1974 to return to Greece after [[Metapolitefsi|democracy had been restored]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Akten |first1=Serta\u00e7 |last2=Alan |first2=G\u00fcls\u00fcm |title=Yunanistan erken genel se\u00e7imleri ile ilgili bilmeniz gereken her \u015fey |url=https://tr.euronews.com/2019/07/03/yunanistan-erken-genel-secime-gidiyor-anketlere-gore-merkez-sag-onde |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=[[Euronews]] (T\u00fcrk\u00e7e) |date=July 4, 2019}}</ref> Later, Mitsotakis described the first six months of his life as [[Political prisoner|political imprisonment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dimokratiki.gr/22-07-2016/ti-apanta-o-kiriakos-mitsotakis-apo-facebook-oti-itan-politikos-kratoumenos-6-minon/|title=\u03a4\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac \u03bf \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf Facebook \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \"\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2, 6 \u03bc\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd\" - \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a1\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5|author=|date=22 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=1 February 2019|via=www.dimokratiki.gr}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, he graduated from [[Athens College]]. From 1986 to 1990, he attended [[Harvard University]] and earned a bachelor's degree in [[social studies]], receiving the [[Thomas T. Hoopes Prize|Hoopes]] and [[Prix Alexis de Tocqueville|Tocqueville]] prizes. From 1992 to 1993 he attended [[Stanford University]], earning a [[Ford Dorsey Master's in International Policy]]. From 1993 to 1995, he attended [[Harvard Business School]] where he earned an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]].<ref name=\"Concordia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.concordia.net/community/kyriakos-mitsotakis/|title=Kyriakos Mitsotakis|author=|date=|website=Concordia|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\nFrom 1990 to 1991 Kyriakos Mitsotakis worked as a [[financial analyst]] at the [[corporate finance]] division of [[Chase Bank]] in London. From 1991 to 1992, Mitsotakis returned to Greece and joined the [[Hellenic Army]] to fulfil his mandatory [[Conscription in Greece|national service]] obligations. From 1995 to 1997, and following the completion of his post-graduate studies, he was employed by the consultancy [[McKinsey & Company]] in London, focusing primarily on the [[telecommunication]]s and [[financial services]] industries. From 1997 to 1999 he worked for Alpha Ventures, a [[private equity]] subsidiary of [[Alpha Bank]], as a senior investment officer, executing venture capital and private equity transactions. In 1999 he founded NBG Venture Capital, the private equity and venture capital subsidiary of the [[National Bank of Greece]], and acted as its [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] until April 2003, when he resigned to pursue a career in politics, managing its portfolio and executing transactions in Greece and the [[Balkans]].<ref name=\"Concordia\" />\n\nIn January 2003 he was nominated by the [[World Economic Forum]] as a global leader of tomorrow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delphiforum.gr/speakers/kyriakos-mitsotakis|title=Kyriakos Mitsotakis - Delphi Economic Forum|author=|date=|website=www.delphiforum.gr|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDuring the [[2000 Greek legislative election|2000 legislative election]], Mitsotakis worked for New Democracy's national campaign. In the [[2004 Greek legislative election|2004 legislative election]], Mitsotakis ran in the [[Athens B (constituency)|Athens B]] constituency, receiving more votes than any other New Democracy candidate in the country and was elected to the [[Hellenic Parliament]].{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nMitsotakis is honorary president of Konstantinos K. Mitsotakis Foundation, aiming at promoting the life and works of [[Konstantinos Mitsotakis]] and at reporting the modern political history of Greece.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn 24 June 2013, Mitsotakis was appointed as the [[Ministry of Administrative Reform and e-Governance (Greece)|Minister of Administrative Reform and e-Governance]] in [[Antonis Samaras]]' cabinet, succeeding [[Antonis Manitakis]]. He served in this position until January 2015. During this time, he pursued comprehensive national reforms by implementing a functional reorganization of institutions, structures and processes. He steadfastly supported the drastic downsizing of the [[Public Sector]] and the structural reform of the tax administration.\n\nIn 2015, Mitsotakis served as a parliamentary representative for New Democracy, representing the President of the party in Parliament, as well as the body of the party's Representatives. He was charged with expressing the positions of his party during Parliamentary procedures and discourse, as well as ensuring the proper function of Parliament through a process of checks and balances. In March 2015, he claimed that then-Minister of Finance [[Yanis Varoufakis]] was undermining the Greek negotiations over the [[Third Economic Adjustment Programme for Greece|third bailout programme]], saying: \"Every time he opens his mouth, he creates a problem for the country\u2019s negotiating position.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.ekathimerini.com/168038/article/ekathimerini/news/varoufakis-undermining-greek-negotiations-says-mitsotakis|title = Varoufakis undermining Greek negotiations, says Mitsotakis|last = |first = |date = 9 March 2015|work = Kathimerini|access-date = 20 January 2016|via = }}</ref>\n\n[[File:EPP Summit, Brussels, March 2016 (25834276136).jpg|thumb|left|Mitsotakis and Armenian President [[Serzh Sargsyan]] in 2016]]\nMitsotakis was the first of four New Democracy members to announce their candidacy in the [[New Democracy leadership election, 2015\u201316|leadership election]], declared following the resignation of [[Antonis Samaras]] as party leader and the failure of New Democracy in the [[September 2015 Greek legislative election|September 2015 snap election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.ekathimerini.com/201813/article/ekathimerini/news/mitsotakis-first-to-declare-will-run-for-nd-leadership|title = Mitsotakis first to declare will run for ND leadership|last = |first = |date = 22 September 2015|work = Kathimerini|access-date = 20 January 2016|via = }}</ref> Amongst the other contestants was then-interim leader and former [[Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament]] [[Vangelis Meimarakis]]. According to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', Mitsotakis was \"billed as an outsider in the leadership race\" due to the party establishment's support of Meimarakis' candidacy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/3509ba68-b7dc-11e5-bf7e-8a339b6f2164.html|title = Free-market reformer Mitsotakis wins vote to lead Greece opposition party|last = Hope|first = Kerin|date = 10 January 2016|work = Financial Times|access-date = 19 January 2016|via = }}</ref> Following the first round of voting with no clear winner, Mitsotakis came second, 11% behind Meimarakis.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:EPP Summit, Brussels, March 2017 (33212125861).jpg|thumb|Mitsotakis and Spanish Prime Minister [[Mariano Rajoy]] in 2017]]\nOn 10 January 2016, Mitsotakis was elected president of the [[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]] political party succeeding [[Ioannis Plakiotakis]] (transitional president) with almost 4% difference from opponent [[Vangelis Meimarakis]]. A week following Mitsotakis' election as leader, two opinion polls were published that put New Democracy ahead of [[Syriza]] for the first time in a year.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://news.yahoo.com/greek-opposition-ahead-syriza-first-time-151535112.html|title = Greek opposition ahead of Syriza for first time in a year|last = |first = |date = 17 January 2016|agency= AFP|access-date = 19 January 2016|via = Yahoo News}}</ref>\n\nHis party won 33% of the votes in the European elections in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsit.gr/politikh/apotelesmata-eyroeklogon-2019-idou-i-teliki-katataksi-935-monades-i-diafora-6/2791810/|title=2019 european elections results|last=|first=|date=6 June 2019|website=NewsIt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He managed to win back votes from the [[Golden Dawn (political party)|Golden Dawn]] Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/grece-syriza-devancee-par-la-droite-conservatrice-672771|title=Gr\u00e8ce. Syriza devanc\u00e9e par la droite conservatrice|date=May 27, 2019|website=L'Humanit\u00e9|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref> Following the election results, the Hellenic Parliament was dissolved and a snap election was called.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/05/27/greece-headed-to-snap-elections-after-syriza-defeat-in-eu-vote|title=Greece headed to snap elections after Syriza defeat in EU vote|website=www.euronews.com|date=27 May 2019|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Greece==\n\nNew Democracy won a landslide victory in the [[2019 Greek legislative election|2019 legislative election]], scoring 39.85% of votes and securing 158 seats in the [[Hellenic Parliament]]. On 8 July 2019, Greek President [[Prokopis Pavlopoulos]] accepted Tsipras's resignation and tasked Mitsotakis with forming a new government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/07/08/greek-conservative-mitsotakis-sworn-in-as-prime-minister/|title=Greek conservative Mitsotakis sworn in as prime minister|last=Service|first=Reuters News|date=2019-07-08|website=Cyprus Mail|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> Mitsotakis was sworn in as Prime Minister the same day as well.<ref name=guardianjuly8inaug>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/08/kyriakos-mitsotakis-takes-over-greece-pm-new-democracy|title=Mitsotakis takes over as Greece's PM with radical change of style|first=Helena|last=Smith|date=Jul 8, 2019|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=dwjuly8inaug>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/greek-conservative-mitsotakis-sworn-in-as-prime-minister/a-49511142|title=Greek conservative Mitsotakis sworn in as prime minister &#124; DW &#124; 08.07.2019|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=aljazeerajuly8inaug /> On 9 July, the [[Cabinet of Kyriakos Mitsotakis|ministers in his government]] were sworn in.\n[[File:EPP Zagreb Congress in Croatia, 20-21 November 2019 (49099971307).jpg|thumb|Mitsotakis on the EPP [[Zagreb]] Congress, 2019]]\n\n== Personal life ==\nMitsotakis is the younger brother of former [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Greece)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] and [[Mayor of Athens]] [[Dora Bakoyannis]], making him the brother-in-law of the late [[Pavlos Bakoyannis]], who was assassinated by the terrorist group [[Revolutionary Organization 17 November|17 November]] in 1989 and the uncle of [[Kostas Bakoyannis]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/elections/news/greeces-top-family-dynasty-in-bid-for-pm-athens-mayor/|title=Greece's top family dynasty in bid for PM, Athens mayor|date=May 31, 2019|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref> former Regional Governor of [[Central Greece (region)|Central Greece]] and current [[Mayor of Athens]].\n\nMitsotakis is married to [[Mareva Grabowski]], an investment banker with Greek, Polish and Egyptian roots. They have three children, Sophia, Constantine and Daphne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greece.greekreporter.com/2019/07/09/mareva-grabowski-mitsotakis-meet-the-new-first-lady-of-greece/|author=Tasos Kokkinidis|title=Mareva Grabowski-Mitsotakis: Meet the New First Lady of Greece|date=Jul 7, 2019|website=GreekReporter.com|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Greek, he speaks English, French and German.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/140719/new-greek-pm-kyriakos-mitsotakis-is-a-scion-of-one-of-greeces-most-influential-political-families/|title=New Greek PM Kyriakos Mitsotakis is a scion of one of Greece's most influential political families &#124; Neos Kosmos|date=Jul 7, 2019|website=English Edition|accessdate=Jul 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMitsotakis is a member of the [[Greek Orthodox Church]].\n\n==Controversy==\n=== Siemens scandal allegations ===\nIn 2007, it was reported that Mitsotakis was involved in the [[Siemens Greek bribery scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.enet.gr/online/online_text/c%3D110%2Cid%3D74151416%2C43446968%2C15515192%2C21432248%2C79944568%2C37645624%2C44118392 |title=\u0395\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03af\u03b1 - \u03a4\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \"\u0396\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03c2\" |accessdate=2017-05-09 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225084100/http://archive.enet.gr/online/online_text/c%3D110%2Cid%3D74151416%2C43446968%2C15515192%2C21432248%2C79944568%2C37645624%2C44118392 |archivedate=February 25, 2011 }}</ref> However, Mitsotakis has repeatedly denied any involvement and no indication of guilt has so far been proven. The Siemens trial, in which Mitsotakis is not involved, is still pending.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/1174442/ypothesi-siemens-stis-24-febrouariou-arxizei-i-diki|title=\u03a5\u03c0\u03cc\u03b8\u03b5\u03c3\u03b7 Siemens: \u03a3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 24 \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b7 &#124; naftemporiki.gr|date=November 22, 2016|website=www.naftemporiki.gr}}</ref>\n\nElectronic office equipment, call centers, air conditioners etc. worth approx. \u20ac130,000 were received in the period preceding the 2007 elections (June to September 2007) by Mitsotakis from Siemens and two of its subsidiaries. The invoices indicate payment period of up to 60 days, however no part of the amount was paid until February 2008, when part of it was paid, just when the Siemens case was reopened by the courts, and an amount of \u20ac43,850 was paid by check from Mr. Mitsotakis on Monday June 2. Earlier (on 29 May) testimonies had been made about \"donations and grants by Siemens to politicians\" and on 30 May 2008 the prosecutor's investigation took place at the company's offices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.protothema.gr/greece/article/9988/emplokh-kyr-mhtsotakh-sto-skandalo-siemens/|title=\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03ba\u03ac\u03bd\u03b4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf SIEMENS|date=2015-12-23|website=protothema.gr|language=greek|access-date=2008-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kathimerini.gr/324733/article/epikairothta/politikh/106-thlefwnikes-syskeyes-gia-ena-grafeio|title=107 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bb\u03b5\u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c5\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03ad\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1 \u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03af\u03bf|date=2015-12-23|website=kathimerini.gr|language=greek|access-date=2008-06-07}}</ref>\n\n== Venizelos/Mitsotakis family tree ==\n{{Venizelos/Mitsotakis family tree}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website}} {{in lang|en|el}}\n* {{Hellenic Parliament|d0750741-dbb8-4bec-9466-526fe9c11773|cv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antonis Manitakis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Administrative Reform and e-Governance|Minister of Administrative Reform]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nikos Voutsis]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2016\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alexis Tsipras]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alexis Tsipras]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Greece]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ioannis Plakiotakis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New Democracy (Greece)|President of New Democracy]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Katerina Sakellaropoulou]]|as=[[President of Greece|President of the Republic]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Greek order of precedence|Order of precedence of Greece]]<br />''{{small|as Prime Minister}}''|years=}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Konstantinos Tasoulas]]|as=[[Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament|Speaker of the Parliament]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Greece}}\n{{Current Cabinet of Greece}}\n{{Leaders of the Opposition of Greece}}\n{{Leaders of New Democracy}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{NATO leaders}}\n{{Vouli-database}}\n{{Portal bar|Greece|Politics|}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitsotakis, Kyriakos}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Greek bankers]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2004\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2007\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2009\u20132012]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2012 (May)]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2012\u20132014]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2015 (February\u2013August)]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2015\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Greek MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Greece]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Leaders of New Democracy (Greece)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:McKinsey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Administrative Reform and e-Governance of Greece]]\n[[Category:Mitsotakis family|Kyriakos]]\n[[Category:New Democracy (Greece) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Athens]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:587:1111:7800:85c3:9f92:7ff2:73f3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyriakos_Mitsotakis"}
